<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Hold Dialogue With Sports Authorities  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive body of the European Union, is to meet authorities of
sports federations and athlete representatives next week to
discuss what best suits the interests of sports and athletes alike.
</P>
<P>
A total of 54 sports federations including the International
Olympic Committee and the European Olympic Committee as well as
international and continental sports federations will meet members
of the commission and the European Parliament in Brussels next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting is scheduled to discuss and debate issues
ranging from doping, health, welfare of the youngsters to
differences between sports federations and civilian administrative
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also touch upon the argument between the
European Union and sports federations as regards the number of
foreign players European soccer clubs can play in their matches.
</P>
<P>
Viviane Reding, EU commissioner of culture and sports, told
FIFA and UEFA, governing bodies of soccer in the world and in
Europe respectively, that they should not expect a change in the
court ruling that led to free agency and the ending of quotas on
foreign players in soccer leagues in European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
The European Court of Justice ruled in 1995 via the case of
Jean-Marc Bosman that players could switch teams without transfer
fees when their contracts expire.
</P>
<P>
Both FIFA and UEFA want to re-introduce limits on the number of
foreign players clubs can field each match.
</P>
<P>
"The Bosman ruling has been based on the free movement of
people and non discrimination (of the EU Treaty)," said Reding on
Tuesday. "You cannot overrule a court ruling. That is the
principle."
</P>
<P>
One of the negative aspects, however, of the Bosman ruling has
been the decline in youth training and the resulted widening gap
between rich and poor clubs.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner backed a system of educational contracts
between clubs and young talents to make sure grassroots
development survive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
