<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Confirms Cancellation of Mozambique's Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Italy confirmed here Thursday that
his government will write off 2.5 billion U.S. dollars worth of
foreign debt from poor countries, including the debt to Rome owed
by Mozambique, which has been recently attacked by the worst
floods in more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Italian Vice Foreign Minister Franco Danielli told a meeting
called "Summits, Commitments and Cooperation" in Havana, "We need
to interrupt the vicious circle generated by debt."
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the Italian initiative, it will be possible to
obtain the cancellation of the entire restructurable commercial
debts at the Club of Paris," he said.
</P>
<P>
The club was to object the total cancellation of this debt, and
Italy would go ahead with the initiative by covering the remaining
portion, he said.
</P>
<P>
But it does not seem to be the case, as he put it, "the Italian
move has been well received at the club, which has on its part
decided to suspend external debt servicing by Mozambique, a first
step toward the possible cancellation of the debt."
</P>
<P>
However, Danielli noted that eliminating the servicing of debt
will not be sufficient to secure the sustainable development of
poorer countries, for "what we need are new international
strategies for reducing and fighting poverty: a new 'covenant'
based on joint efforts between a rich and a poor world."
</P>
<P>
"All of us feel the need to profoundly restructure the forms of
international cooperation, and Italian cooperation has made very
firm and clear strategic decisions in this direction, making human
development, the reduction of poverty and social exclusion its
focus," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Italian decision comes at a time when all 122 countries
attending the first South Summit of the Group of 77 in Havana are
identifying the burden of foreign debt as one of the main
obstacles to achieving development in the South. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finances Regional Projects to Create New Jobs in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 148 investment
projects in Romania will benefit from financing worth 5.5 million
euros granted by the European Union within the PHARE Regional
Development Program.
</P>
<P>
Through these projects which were presented Thursday at a press
conference and which will benefit from co-financing from Romania's
government, as many as 3,200 jobs will be created.
</P>
<P>
The projects were selected out of a total of 3,029 which were
submitted in September last year at the headquarters of the eight
regional agencies with the support of the National Agency for
Regional Development.
</P>
<P>
According to the leader of the EU assistance programs in
Romania Simon Mordue, the high number of submitted projects and
also their quality are a good thing which demonstrates "not only
the potential which exists in Romania for economic growth and
creation of new jobs but also the high degree of initiative and
commitment which exists at local level."
</P>
<P>
Each project can receive up to 62,500 euros and European
Commission chief in Romania Fokion Fotiadis hoped that 10,000 new
jobs would be created at the finalization of all projects.
</P>
<P>
"The good answer received at this selection of projects makes
us believe that Romania would be capable of obtaining the sum of
75,000,000 euros existing in the PHARE budget for the year 2000
for Romania," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
