<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Not to Request Pardon For Possible Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Thursday that he would not ask for any pardon from his
successor to avoid prosecution in the Monica Lewinsky
investigation or any other scandal.
</P>
<P>
"I don't have any interest in that," Clinton told the American
Society of Newspaper Editors. "I don't want one and I am prepared
to stand before any bar of justice I have to stand before."
</P>
<P>
The question of a presidential pardon arose after recent
statements by Robert W. Ray, the independent counsel, who said he
had hired additional prosecutors and was considering whether to
indict Clinton after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
Ray replaced Kenneth W. Starr last October as the independent
counsel to investigate Clinton's affairs with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that his battle against his impeachment by Congress
in the sex scandal "saved the Constitution" and he is "proud of"
it.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was impeached by the House on perjury and obstruction
charges, then acquitted by the Senate a year ago.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that he had made "a terrible mistake" in
behavior in his affair with Lewinsky and he was "deeply regretful,
" but he has paid for it.
</P>
<P>
"We all pay for our mistakes," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made it clear that his president library would not
ignore his impeachment by the House and trial and acquittal in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
"We have to deal with it, it is an important part" of his
presidency, Clinton said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
