<HEADLINE> U.S. Justice Delays Turnover of Cuban Boy to Father </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The department said that it has been asked by the 11th Circuit
Court of Appeals to forestall any enforcement action in the matter
of Elian, pending their review of a motion for a temporary
injunction filed by attorneys for the Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
The boy's relatives asked the appeals court in Atlanta to issue
an emergency order blocking any attempt by the government to
remove Elian from the family, pending further legal moves.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Elian's Miami relatives defied a government
order to turn over the boy by a deadline while the U.S.
authorities said they will not use force to take the boy away.
</P>
<P>
Elian's great uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, who has taken the custody
of the boy in Miami, had been instructed to deliver Elian to an
airport near Miami at 2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
Also Thursday, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno said that there
won't be any immediate action by federal marshals to remove the
six-year-old boy from the home of the boy's Florida relatives and
return him to his father.
</P>
<P>
Reno, who met the family members Wednesday night, told
reporters in Miami that if the boy's relatives didn't work out a
solution, the government would take action in a "reasonable,
measured way."
</P>
<P>
"I am prepared to enforce the law, but I want to be clear that
if we are compelled to enforce our order, we intend to do so in a
reasonable, measured way, the approach that we have always taken
in this matter," she said.
</P>
<P>
After failing to get a deal with the family during the meeting
attended by the Cuban boy Wednesday, Reno ordered them to bring
him to the Opa-locka airport outside Miami at 2 p.m. for a flight
to Washington.
</P>
<P>
An Associated Press report said 50 police cars ringed the
airport and 200 officers were deployed to the area.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 last year after his mother and
other 11 people died when their boat capsized in the Atlantic off
Florida. His relatives in Miami then took custody of him,
insisting that the boy should remain in the United States even
after the boy's father came to the U.S. to pick up his son.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Justice Department ruled earlier this year that the
boy belongs to his father and should be returned to Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
