<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Economic Outlook Bright: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A report on the world economy
published Wednesday by the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
projects a positive scenario for Brazil for this and next year.
</P>
<P>
The IMF study received here showed that the Brazilian gross
domestic product (GDP) will grow 4 percent this year and 4.5
percent the next, while its inflation rate will spin around 7 and
5 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Brazil has already recovered from the
turbulence which occurred at the beginning of 1999, when the
effects of the Russian crisis were having their heyday, taking the
Brazilian government to devalue the real before the time expected.
</P>
<P>
The IMF says that this recovery has been led by agriculture,
industrial production, and exports.
</P>
<P>
According to the IMF forecasts, Brazilian exports will increase
this year, while the current account deficit will be reduced and
completely covered by the arrival of direct foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
The maintenance of the present budget policy and the
implementation of reforms to public administration and to the
social security system, together with an ample program of
privatization, must improve Brazil's access to international
credit, according to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF warned that the deceleration of the economy
and the rising trend of the rates of interest in the United States
could produce negative impacts on the recovery of the Brazilian
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebel ELN Starts 10-day Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Holy Week cease fire announced
Wednesday by Colombian rebel National Liberation Army (ELN)
Central Command (COCE) started Thursday at 00:01 hours and will
end at 24:00 of Sunday, April 23.
</P>
<P>
Colombians can move around Thursday without fear, thanks to the
suspension of military operations in the country.
</P>
<P>
The decision implies the temporary suspension of the false
checkpoints for the control of the traffic in the country roads,
in which the rebels usually take hostages and burn buses and
trucks.
</P>
<P>
The guerrilla group will also release the five crew members of
an Avianca airline plane that the rebels hijacked one year ago.
</P>
<P>
The airliner hijacking was the second of a series of three mass
kidnappings that the rebels used to press the government of
President Andres Pastrana to establish a neutral zone of
distension that would permit them to start a convocation of the
National Peace Convention.  
</P>
