<HEADLINE> U.S. Appeals Court Issues Temporary Stay for Cuban Boy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Deputy Court Clerk Chris Basnett from the 11th Circuit Court of
Appeals said the stay was issued shortly after 3 p.m. EDT, one
hour after the government deadline passes.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Justice Department announced earlier on Thursday that
it has agreed to delay any enforcement action to take six-year-old
Cuban boy from his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the department said that it has been asked by
the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals to forestall any enforcement
action in the matter of Elian, pending their review of a motion
for a temporary injunction filed by attorneys for the Miami
relatives.
</P>
<P>
The boy's relatives asked the appeals court in Atlanta to issue
an emergency order blocking any attempt by the government to
remove Elian from the family, pending further legal moves.
</P>
<P>
Elian's great uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, who has taken the custody
of the boy in Miami, had been instructed to deliver Elian to an
airport near Miami at 2 p.m. EDT. Instead, he filed the emergency
appeal.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 last year after his mother and
other 11 people died when their boat capsized in the Atlantic off
Florida. His relatives in Miami then took custody of him,
insisting that the boy should remain in the United States even
after the boy's father came to the U.S. to pick up his son.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Justice Department ruled earlier this year that the
boy belongs to his father and should be returned to Cuba. 
</P>
