<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Economic Prospect Upbeat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's economy is
expected to grow by 3.8 percent this year and four percent next
year, South African Press Association reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The forecasts were released by the International Monetary
Fund's (IMF's) World Economic Outlook, which attributed South
Africa's economic growth to rising European demand for the
country's exports, higher metals prices and effective fiscal
management.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also said South Africa's inflation rate is projected at
4.7 percent this year and will rise to 5.7 percent next year and
the country's unemployment rate is close to 40 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the IMF predicted that economic growth in Africa as
a whole will bounce back to 4.4 percent this year from 2.2
percent last year and will hold steady next year.
</P>
<P>
"A rebound of activity in three of the largest economies,
namely Algeria, Nigeria and South Africa, is expected to lead this
recovery, but also significant is the continuing strong
performance projected for many of the smaller countries," the IMF
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
