<HEADLINE> ECOWAS to Hold Mini-Summit on Second Monetary Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A mini-summit of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) would be held in the
Ghanaian capital next week to adopt a plan of action for the
introduction of a second monetary zone in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The summit is to be attended by heads of state from Ghana,
Gambia, Liberia, Sierra Leone and Nigeria, said an ECOWAS official
here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting would also approve a task force to facilitate the
introduction of the zone, parallel to the existing West African
Franc (CFA) zone operated by the Francophone ECOWAS members, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, both zones are expected to be merged
into a single sub-regional currency by 2004.
</P>
<P>
Guinea, the only Francophone ECOWAS country, which does not
operate the CFA franc currency, would also attend the summit
scheduled for April 20, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the 16-member organization endorsed the second
monetary zone, which is due to come into force by 2003, at their
22nd summit in December last year in Lome, the capital of Togo.
</P>
<P>
The mini-summit, a follow-up to the ministerial meeting held in
Abuja in February, would also approve a work program and
operational budget for the task force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
