<HEADLINE> S. African Competition Laws to Come Under Spotlight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's controversial
new competition laws, which have already twice been challenged in
the courts since coming into being last November, will come under
the spotlight at a conference in Midrand north of Johannesburg
next week.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference, which starts on Monday, will bring
together representatives from the private sector, government
regulatory authorities as well as international experts and
leading economists to discuss the issue, the South African Press
Association reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Keynote speakers will include Trade and Industry Minister Alec
Erwin and Public Enterprises Minister Jeff Radebe.
</P>
<P>
The most recent case concerning the Competition Laws was an
appeal case by the country's largest bank, Stanbic, against a
ruling by the High Court that the new Competition Act has no role
in the proposed hostile takeover of Stanbic by its smaller rival
Nedcor bank.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court of Appeal in Bloemfontein upheld a High
Court decision, ruling that the merger must be adjudicated in
terms of the Banks Act and that the competition authorities merely
have to be consulted in terms of the Competition Act.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin has made it clear that
it was never the intention that the Competition Act play second
fiddle to other regulatory legislation, but rather that it serve
as the prime legislation in competition matters.
</P>
<P>
"Although the recent decision by the Supreme Court of Appeal
has settled to some extent the jurisdictional debate on bank and
insurance mergers, it has also highlighted the urgent need for a
holistic review of the regulatory framework in South Africa," the
Competition Commission says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
