<HEADLINE> Canadian PM Denies Taking in Palestinian Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien has denied press reports that his country would take in
some 15,000 Palestinians refugees as part of a solution to the
refugee issue in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian embassy here released a statement Thursday saying "
There is no agreement with Israel and no undertaking with any party
for Canada to take in Palestinian refugees."
</P>
<P>
The Canadian leader also stressed that the Palestinian refugee
question has to be resolved by the parties concerned in the region,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued after press reports quoted an unnamed
Israeli official as saying on Wednesday that Chretien had promised
to take in 15,000 Palestinian refugees during his talks on Sunday
with his Israeli counterpart Ehud Barak in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Chretien will arrive in Amman on Friday for a three-day official
visit to hold talks with King Abdullah Bin Hussein and Prime
Minister Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh on bilateral talks and the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Canada has been chairing the Multilateral Peace Process Refugee
Working Group since its establishment in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Chretien stressed that as the chair country, it would be "
inappropriate for Canada to impose its views or prejudge the
outcome of negotiations to resolve this difficult issue."
</P>
<P>
The fate of millions of Palestinian refugees is one of the
thorny issues in the on-going final status peace talks between
Israel and the Palestinians, alongside borders, Jewish settlements
and the future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Over 3 million Palestinians have fled their home since the
creation of Israel in 1948 as a result of wars between the Jewish
state and its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Currently Jordan is home to some 1.2 million Palestinian
refugees, most of them have been granted Jordanian citizenship.
</P>
<P>
However, Jordan supported the Palestinian refugees in the
kingdom to choose between returning to their homeland or asking for
compensation from parties concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
