<HEADLINE> Russian Ministers Urges Ratification of START II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov met with lawmakers
Thursday ahead of debates in the State Duma lower house of
parliament on ratification of the START II treaty.
</P>
<P>
In a closed-door hearing, the ministers urged Duma deputies to
ratify the long-delayed Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty with the
United States as a way to rid of the aging nuclear warheads and
concentrate funds on new weapons, Russian media reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty signed with Washington in 1993, the two
countries will cut their nuclear warheads each from some 6,000 to
3,000-3,500 by 2007.
</P>
<P>
Duma deputies are scheduled to start debating in the lower
house Friday morning and then vote on whether to approve the
document, which was ratified by the U.S. Senate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"I think concern over the future of Russia and its security
will prevail and deputies will vote in favor," Sergeyev told
reporters after addressing the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
"We've little room to maneuver," he said. "The reality is such
that it is essential to ratify START II and move on to START III."
</P>
<P>
Many of the 450 deputies were reportedly won over by the
ministers' statements in the conviction that Moscow should not
spend money from the already meager coffer on "arms eaten away by
rust," said Lyubov Sliska, the Duma's first deputy speaker, in an
interview with the ORT public television.
</P>
<P>
"It is better to create new technologies, missile systems, such
as Topol-M," she said. Russia has already deployed two 10-rocket
batches of the new-generation missile system.
</P>
<P>
Most observers predict that START II will clear the State Duma
Friday, now that the Communist Party, which staunchly opposes
ratification, wields far less influence in the chamber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
