<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank: Goal of Halving Poverty Attainable, But Difficult </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The goal of halving by 2015
the proportion of the world's people who live in extreme poverty
can still be reached if economic growth resumes without further
increase in inequality, but achieving the goal will be difficult,
the World Bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, in its World Development Indicators 2000 (WDI),
said its annual statistical portrait of people and the state of
their world, a sixth of the world's population -- primarily the
people of North America, Europe, and Japan -- received nearly 80
percent of world income, an average of 70 U.S. dollars per day, in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank said, the 57 percent of the world's
population in the 63 poorest countries received only 6 percent of
world income, an average of less than 2 dollars per day.
</P>
<P>
In East Asia, "the proportion and number of people living in
extreme poverty has fallen sharply since 1987, mainly because of
progress in China," the bank said. However, in South Asia, the
number of people in extreme poverty rose from 495 million to 522
million, while in Sub-Saharan Africa the number of very poor
people increased by some 48 million to 291 million.
</P>
<P>
On globalization, the World Bank said the numbers in the WDI
underline that while globalization is creating new opportunities
for the poorest people in the world to improve their lives, it has
also brought new risks that could further widen the immense gap
between the haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
"In general, despite the setback in the late 1990s, the world's
economy continues to become more integrated, and developing
countries are realizing the benefits. Lower trade barriers in
industrialized countries have stimulated developing country
exports, creating the jobs and economic growth needed for
sustained poverty reduction," it noted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to debt relief and aid, the World Bank said more
rapid reductions in poverty will require improved policies in
developing countries, especially those that are lagging farthest
behind, as well as increased support from the industrialized
countries for poor countries that adopt the necessary reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves Republican Budget for Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Republicans pushed through the
U.S. House Thursday a final budget of 1.83 trillion U.S. dollars
for next year that calls for tax cuts, debt reduction and extra
money for defense, education and medical research.
</P>
<P>
The House passed the measure on a near party-line 220-208 vote,
setting up likely final approval by the Senate later in the day.
President Bill Clinton does not have to sign the plan, which sets
spending and tax targets for fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
But none of the subsequent 13 annual spending bills which
actually provide the money, or any tax bill, will become law
without the president's signature. With Republicans planning
deeper tax cuts and less spending than Democrats prefer, the
election-year battle lines were already clear.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, in a speech to the American Society of Newspaper
Editors, said the Republican budget was "loaded with exploding tax
breaks and untenable cuts in critical investments."
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to veer from the proven path onto a trail of
unmet obligations, unrealistic cuts and unnecessary giveaways. We
can't squander the moment by squandering the surplus," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Republican plan calls for at least 150 billion dollars in
tax cuts through fiscal 2005, and up to an estimated 215 billion
dollars, depending on how much economic growth occurs over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
Clinton wants 99 billion dollars in tax cuts over the period,
plus 96 billion dollars in higher taxes on tobacco and some
corporate transactions.
</P>
<P>
Like Clinton, the Republicans would set aside the entire Social
Security surplus, about 1 trillion dollars over the next five
years, to reduce the publicly held debt. If achieved, many
economists say that would put downward pressure on interest rates
and spur the economy. Of the 5.7-trillion-dollar national debt, 3.
6 trillion dollars are held by the public.
</P>
<P>
The Republican budget also sets aside up to 40 billion dollars
over five years for creation of prescription drug benefits for
Medicare recipients or other changes in the program. It does not,
however, require action on such a program.
</P>
<P>
The budget calls for 311 billion dollars for defense, or about
5 billion dollars more than Clinton wants.
</P>
<P>
And it sets about 289 billion dollars for many domestic
programs, roughly 30 billion dollars less than the president
proposed. That includes proposed increases for schools, veterans
and research, which will have to await the coming spending bills.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the budget covers interest payments on the federal
debt and automatically paid benefits like Social Security,
Medicare and Medicaid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
