<HEADLINE> Food Aid for Mozambican Flood Victims Low on Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) has
warned that the emergency food stocks for flood victims in
southern and central Mozambique may soon run out if the allocation
of more funds is not speeded up.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambique News Agency Thursday quoted WFP spokesman Inyene
Udoyen as saying that there are only about 5,000 tons of food
left, which is enough for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment we are using stocks that were meant for
development projects, such as 'food for work' schemes in areas
vulnerable to disasters, the project for building schools with the
support of the World Bank, and the food intended for school
meals," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that his organization is expecting to receive a further
10,000 tons, which will just be sufficient until mid-May.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman called for urgency in the granting of funds, to
compensate for the time it takes for the suppliers to deliver the
goods and the time- consuming rules imposed for the disbursement
of funds.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the donors will respond to the appeal for an
allocation of 30 million U.S. dollars so that we can respond to
the needs of the people affected by the floods in various parts of
the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Udoyen added that the WFP has been conducting bilateral
negotiations with donors, since the launching of the last updated
appeal by the Mozambican government on March 22.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the May conference (which is to take place in
Rome) will be the big opportunity for the donors to announce their
contributions," he said, stressing that there should be a
response, otherwise stocks will run out.
</P>
<P>
He said the WFP is preparing, together with local
non-government organizations and district administrations, various
actions for resettling people displaced by the floods.
</P>
<P>
These include the urgent rehabilitation of about 1,000
kilometers of roads and several bridges to allow access to
isolated areas, so that food can be distributed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, spokesperson for the National Disasters Management
Institute (INGC) Antonio Macheve also complained of the slow donor
response.
</P>
<P>
"Our concern is the need for money to pay for the present
expenses. What is easily quantifiable, at the moment, is the food
component, where the WFP needs 30 million U.S. dollars, but it is
also necessary to take into account resettlement, which has
already started, and logistics," he said.
</P>
<P>
About 490,000 people are still in accommodation centers, he
said, adding that about 650,000 people in all will need assistance
during the next six months.
</P>
<P>
"We need more assistance for us to be able to respond to the
needs," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
