<HEADLINE> Iran Promises Fair Trial of Jews Accused of Espionage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian judicial official on
Thursday promised a "fair, lawful and impartial" trial of the 13
Jews arrested on espionage charges, saying there is no difference
between Muslims and Jews before law.
</P>
<P>
"All the accused will be treated in the same way according to
the law and no one in Iran will be on trial because of their
opinions," Hussein Ali Amiri, head of the Justice Department of the
southern Fars province, told a press conference in the provincial
capital of Shiraz.
</P>
<P>
He said the first session of the trial of the Jews was held "in
a congenial atmosphere among the judge, accused and their
attorneys" Thursday morning in Shiraz, the center of Iran's 35,000-
strong Jewish community, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door trial adjourned Thursday noon and was postponed
till May 1 upon the request of a defense lawyer as the timing of
the trial coincided with Passover, a Jewish feast.
</P>
<P>
The families of eight Jews have appointed defense lawyers, the
court designated lawyers for two others, while the three who were
released on bail have not appointed any lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyers called for a postponement of the trial as they
have limited time to go through details of the case, which has
aroused grave concerns from the U.S., Israel and other European
countries.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Iranian Jews along with eight Muslims were arrested in
March and April last year on charges of spying for the United
States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Israel have denied any link between their
intelligence services and the Iranian Jews, and urged Iran to
release them since their arrest. But Tehran has rejected the appeal
as "interference" in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
On the likelihood that some of the accused would face the death
penalty, Amiri said the judge would act independently and any
specific ruling cannot be predicted.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that the ruling would be fair and based on the
law. "All the accused expressed satisfaction with the way they were
treated," he said, adding that four of the accused confessed to
their crime in the first court session and asked for leniency.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the case has not been completed for all
the accused and the judge would only rule on that portion of the
case which has been completed.
</P>
<P>
He said the trial was held behind closed doors for national
security concerns.
</P>
<P>
The accused are of different professions including university
professors, teachers and entrepreneurs, he said, currently 10 of
the accused are in detention while the rest, including three Jews
and eight Muslims have been released on bail.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the representative of the Jewish community at the
Iranian Majlis (parliament) Manuchehr Eliasi said that it is not
important for the families of the defendants whether the court
hearing is held in public or in camera, but the important issue is
to conduct a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to IRNA, he expressed hope that the defendants would be
cleared of the charges. The charge of espionage against the
defendants is likely to have become weaker, but another charge
brought against them is acts against national security, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
