<HEADLINE> Iraq Protests to U.N. Over U.S., British Aggressions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has protested to the U.N.
over the continued bombings and airspace violations by the U.S. and
British warplanes from April 1-7, and urged the U.N. to intervene
to halt such aggressions, the official Iraqi News Agency (INA)
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In two letters to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
president of the U.N. Security Council separately, Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tareq Aziz said that during the seven days, the U.S.
and British aircraft made 202 armed sorties, 58 from Turkey and 144
from Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, over the southern and northern
provinces of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British planes bombed civilian and service
facilities on April 6, 14 civilians were killed and 19 others
injured, representing one of the heaviest casualties Iraq has
suffered since December 1998, when the U.S. and Britain launched
the Operation Desert Fox air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The Iraqi government vehemently rejects the so-called no-fly
zones imposed unilaterally by the U.S. and Britain under feeble
pretexts to justify their aggressions on Iraq," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz urged Annan and president of the U.N. Security Council to
intervene to halt the aggressions against Iraq, said the INA.
</P>
<P>
The so-called no-fly zones were set up after the Gulf War, with
the claimed aim of protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite
Muslims in the south from possible attacks by the Iraqi government
troops.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has never recognized the legality of the air exclusion
zones, which were not directly covered by any U.N. Security Council
resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
