<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Yemeni Parliament
Speaker Sheikh Abdullah Al-Ahmar on Thursday renewed a call for
lifting the decade-old U.N. economic sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Our demand to lift the sanctions on the Iraqi people is an Arab
request. It is a call made in every occasion to help the helpless
Iraqis," said Al-Ahmar at a news conference held here during his
four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
But he underlined that Kuwait "has nothing to do with the
sanctions, it was a decision by the United Nations and the United
States."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed harsh economic sanctions against Iraq
since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait. And the Iraqi government has
been drumming up support from the international community for the
lifting of the sanctions which hit the ordinary Iraqi people
hardest.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahmar added that there is "no link between Kuwait's demand
for the release of its prisoners in Iraq and the embargo on Iraq.
It's a U.N. decision."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to over 600 Kuwaiti and non-Kuwaiti nationals
who Kuwait insists are still held in Iraqi jails. Baghdad denied
the allegation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Yemeni official reaffirmed Sanaa's readiness to
help free the alleged Kuwaiti prisoners. "We have always emphasized
that we are ready to play any role to release the prisoners," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The visit to Kuwait by Al-Ahmar, who heads a delegation of
government ministers and lawmakers, is the first of its kind since
the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait which touched off the Gulf War in
1991.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait cut off its diplomatic ties with Yemen after Sanaa showed
sympathy with Iraq during the war.
</P>
<P>
Their relations were fully restored in May last year, when Yemen
reopened its embassy in Kuwait after a nine-year closure. 
</P>
