<HEADLINE> Turkey Needs Nuclear Energy: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will in no way give up the
choice of nuclear energy, said Turkish Minister of Energy and
Natural Resources Cumhur Ersumer on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ersumer made the remarks while addressing the "Energy Sources"
symposium in Canakkale, a city at the mouth of the Dardanelles
Strait, reported Turkey's Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey needs nuclear energy and other energies for
the country's development, noting that nuclear energy has made
significant contributions to the development of industrialized
nations.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, poor in fossil energy, decided several years ago to
build its first nuclear power station in Akkuyu, a Mediterranean
port city in southern Turkey, a move that has ever since aroused a
severe controversy between pros and cons in the country.
</P>
<P>
Three international consortia have been bidding for the 5-
billion-U.S.-dollar Akkuyu plant project.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Electricity Generation Utility (TEAS) has postponed
for several times announcement on the winner of the contract and
decided last Friday again to extend their bids until April 21.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Treasury had refused to provide a
guarantee for the financing of the costly nuclear project in view
of the current economic stability and disinflation program.
</P>
<P>
Ersumer acknowledged the fact that there are people who oppose
development of nuclear energy and they have stepped up their anti-
nuclear efforts.
</P>
<P>
On other energy options, the minister said that "There are
projects on solar energy and we are discussing them."
</P>
<P>
"Turkey imports 90 percent of natural gas and 95 percent of oil
the country consumes every year. We should evaluate all our energy
sources," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
