<HEADLINE> Russians Support Chechen Campaign Despite High Toll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The campaign against Chechen
rebels remains popular among the Russians despite mounting
casualties suffered by federal troops in the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent opinion poll conducted by the APRII
agency for regional political research, 60 percent of the surveyed
last Monday said the federal troops must carry the operation in
Chechnya through to victory, the Interfax news agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Only 22 percent of the 1,600 adults questioned in 90 cities,
towns and villages of 49 Russian regions said they were sure that
talks should start with the Chechens. The poll has an error margin
of 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The popularity of the military actions in Chechnya seemed not
to have been dented by mounting casualties among federal troops in
the North Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
According to General Valery Manilov, first deputy chief of the
Russian General Staff, a total of 2,119 federal servicemen have
been killed and 6,253 wounded in the anti-terrorist campaign.
</P>
<P>
Manilov told a Thursday news conference that of those killed, 1,
396 were from Defense Ministry units and 723 came from the
Interior Forces.
</P>
<P>
Russia launched the military assaults on Chechen rebels last
September following waves of armed Chechen incursions into
neighboring Dagestan and a spate of apartment explosions that left
some 300 people dead in Moscow and two other cities. Chechen
militants were accused of being behind the blasts.
</P>
<P>
The war in Chechnya was in its final stage, with all principal
Chechen separatist forces beaten and federal troops wiping out "
remnants of bandit formations," Manilov said.
</P>
<P>
He said the federal forces were killing up to 30 rebels and
destroying 10 to 12 rebel bases or ammunition depots every day.
</P>
</TEXT>
