<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Lends Vaccine to Japan, S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Thursday that the European Union has decided to lend to Japan and
South Korea vaccines to combat the outbreak of foot-and-mouth
disease in cattle.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation bloc, said
that the vaccine lend would be made from the EU antigen bank and
the commission's decision to lend followed a request from the
Japanese and South Korean authorities.
</P>
<P>
The presence of the foot-and-mouth disease in cattle was first
discovered and confirmed in Japan on March 24 this year and in
South Korea on April 2.
</P>
<P>
One million doses of the vaccine will be sent to Japan with the
first delivery scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Like the EU, the Japanese and South Korean authorities follow a
non-vaccination policy against the disease and vaccines are only
used in case of emergency.
</P>
<P>
The two Asian countries will replace the vaccines provided by
the EU within six months and the EU has important reserves of the
virus antigen which is the basis for the production of the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
The European Union maintains a bank with virus antigens
equivalent to about 30 million vaccine doses against the foot-and-
mouth disease for use in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
The foot-and-mouth disease is a highly contagious viral disease,
known to cause significant economic losses to cattle farmers. In
general, an outbreak of the disease immediately leads to
restrictions on international trade in livestock and in products
such as meat, milk and certain cheeses originating from the
country affected.
</P>
<P>
The disease in animals, however, does not pose any threat to
human health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
