<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Aid Pledges Almost Match Estimates: EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Union said Thursday
that international food aid pledges almost matched up with the
estimates about the shortage in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
EU officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, told the
press that satellite images and field trips helped international
observers to make the estimates of Ethiopian food shortage at 821,
000 tons for this year.
</P>
<P>
So far, total donor pledges are over 800,000 tons, of which the
15-nation European bloc pledged to provide more than half. The EU
food aid to arrive in Ethiopia in 2000 totals 432,526 tons,
according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
Of the amount, 282,526 tons are being offloaded, shipped or
procured with the remaining 150,000 tons in the process of being
allocated.
</P>
<P>
From all donors, total shipments of food aid expected to arrive
in Ethiopia between now and July is 504,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The EU food aid will be channeled to three relief programs, the
non-governmental organizations, the World Food Program and the
Ethiopian government, the officials added.
</P>
<P>
Despite international efforts, food rations per head per month
in Ethiopia is only six kilograms as against the targeted 12.5
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The current food shortage in the African country has been
caused by a poor harvest due to the lack of rains, the EU
officials explained.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has been a major supplier of food aid to
Ethiopia in the past 25 years, during which period 38 percent of
all EU aid to Ethiopia has been used for food aid activities.
</P>
<P>
Over the past four years alone, 250 million euros (240 million
U.S. dollars) have been spent on food aid for Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
