<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: South Has Better Understanding on Gobalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The word "globalization" is one of
the most frequently used words by leaders from developing
countries who are attending a summit here, but they are finding
themselves with a better understanding on what the word means in
the world economy and politics.
</P>
<P>
The more thorough understanding was achieved as some 60 heads
of state and government, together with senior officials from 122
countries, gathered in the Cuban capital of Havana for the first
South Summit of the Group of 77 (G-77) in the body's 36-year
history.
</P>
<P>
The South Summit came at the turn of century when many
developing countries, small and weak ones in particular, are being
marginalized in the globalization process, and the gap between the
haves and the have-nots is widening in economic and social
development.
</P>
<P>
South and world Leaders took advantage of the historic event to
study the two sides of globalization, including its impact on the
developing world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many countries agreed that the pace of globalization
was quickened in the wake of the rapid progress in technology,
including information technology. However, they also realized that
interdependence is increasing among countries and the world is
linked as a whole in its economic development.
</P>
<P>
In fact, globalization, through trade, investment, capital
flows and advancements in technology, has had a profound impact on
all aspects of international relations.
</P>
<P>
Both Cuban President Fidel Castro, leader of the host country
to the summit, and Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo, chairman
of G-77, agreed that the rich and poor countries are traveling
together in the tide of globalization.
</P>
<P>
"We are on the same boat," Obasanjo said, referring to the
impact of globalization on the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Applying the similar metaphor, Castro said, "Gobalization is an
objective reality underlining the fact that we are all passengers
on the same vessel, that is, this planet where we all live. But,
passengers on this vessel are traveling in very different
conditions."
</P>
<P>
"Eighty-five percent of the passengers on this ship are crowded
together in its dirty hold suffering hunger, diseases and
helplessness," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rich are enjoying access to the Internet, cell phones and
global communication networks while the poor are living from hand
to mouth.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, this vessel is carrying too much injustice to
remain afloat and it pursues such an irrational and senseless
route that it cannot call on a safe port," he said. "This vessel
seems destined to clash with an iceberg. If that happened, we
would all sink with it."
</P>
<P>
On the impact of globalization, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said at the prestigious Havana University, "Only a
relatively small number of countries are enjoying these games.
Many millions of people are excluded, left behind in squalor."
</P>
<P>
A lot of developing countries, at the summit, cried out to see
globalization as a powerful and dynamic force for strengthening
cooperation and development. Apart from increasing the
vulnerabilities of the South countries, the process presents
opportunities as well as risks and challenges.
</P>
<P>
"To those already enjoying them, the benefits of globalization
are clear: faster economic growth, higher living standards, the
rapid spread of new technology and modern management skills,"
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Many developing countries are already showing the way -- India
with its booming software industry; Costa Rica with its microchip
exports; Mauritius, using the Internet to position its textile
industry globally; Mali, using an Internet to give its citizens
more effective administrative services. These are just a few
examples.
</P>
<P>
However, developing countries has a really long way to go
before they can largely merge into the mainstream of global
economy.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve the strategic goal, many South countries
came to realize that the North-South relations should be further
improved in addition to the existing hard efforts to strengthen
cooperation among themselves and set up a more just and fair
international political and economic system.
</P>
<P>
The eradication of poverty and the attainment of sustainable
development in the South demands "a constructive and purposeful
relationship" between the developed North and the developing South,
Thabo Mbeki, chairman of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM), said.
</P>
<P>
"Speedy movement forward towards their accomplishment requires
a constructive and purposeful relationship between ourselves and
the countries of the North," he said.
</P>
<P>
The North-South relationship must address "the alleviation of
the debt burden carried by many of our countries, including its
cancellation, an effective mechanism to ensure a substantial
increase in capital flows into the developing economies as this is
a prerequisite for development," he said.
</P>
<P>
The focus should include the reversal of the trend resulting in
a sharp drop in official development assistance, the opening of
the markets of the developed countries to their products,
including agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
This should also cover the transfer of technology. If the
technology divided between North and South grows in the wake of
rapid advances in communication and bio-technology, then all will
suffer and not just the developing world.
</P>
<P>
The summit is expected to adopt the Havana Declaration and the
Program of Action, which will be conducive to the solidarity among
developing countries for stronger cooperation in order to
collectively face the challenge of globalization, observers here
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
