<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Police Calls for Public Help in Fighting Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Senior Assistant Commissioner of
the Zimbabwean Police John Zvimba Thursday urged the public to
cooperate in the fight against corruption by not offering gifts to
the police.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a passout parade for 291 officers who have
completed a six- month training program, Zvimba said the public
should report any case of corruption using hotline and suggestion
boxes.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to warn you to desist from the temptation of
being corrupted by the society you will be policing," he told the
officers.
</P>
<P>
The police, he said, need cooperation from the public to
develop appropriate law and order management tactics.
</P>
<P>
"The duty of maintaining law and order depends for its success
on the amount of public support and cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it is important for policemen to know the extent to
which they could exercise their powers without infringing upon the
rights of individuals.
</P>
<P>
"Your training included an element of human rights to ensure
that as law enforcement agents you treat those you come in contact
with dignity and respect," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the police force has set a high standard of discipline
and reputation which should be maintained locally and outside the
country.
</P>
<P>
The police force would not hesitate to terminate services of
members whose discipline and performance are below standard, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Since February this year the police has suspended 55 officers
from the Harare province from active duty for corruption and
incompetence.
</P>
<P>
Last year, at least two officers were dismissed for corruption
every month from the 10,000 strong force, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
