<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Qualifies for Enhanced HIPC: WB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced on
Wednesday that Mozambique has qualified for an additional 600
million dollars worth of debt relief under the terms of the
enhanced HIPC (Heavily Indebted poor Countries) debt relief
initiative.
</P>
<P>
The International Development Association (IDA -- the Bank's
soft loans affiliate) and the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
have agreed to support "a comprehensive debt reduction package for
Mozambique", said the World Bank in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique reached the HIPC "completion point" on June 30 last
year: with the debt relief package being 3.7 billion U.S. dollars
in nominal terms (1. 7 billion U.S. dollars in net present value
terms - the net present value is the amount that would have to be
invested now to pay off the debt).
</P>
<P>
The new relief under enhanced HIPC brings the total up to 4.3
billion U. S. dollars in nominal terms and almost two billion U.S.
dollars in net present value terms.
</P>
<P>
This will push Mozambique's debt stock down to about 750
million U.S. dollars (net present value). In fact, once all the
calculations are made, the real figure for the debt stock may be
considerably lower, since several creditor nations (Britain,
Portugal and Finland, for example) have taken the unilateral
decision to cancel all or much of the debts owed by Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
But, just as with the original HIPC, there are conditions
attached to enhanced HIPC.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique will only receive the full amount of relief under
enhanced HIPC "when it satisfies the requirements for a floating
completion point, including adoption of a participatory poverty
reduction strategy paper", according to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
For Mozambique to obtain the full benefits of enhanced HIPC,
there must also be "maintenance of a stable macroeconomic
environment, as evidenced by satisfactory performance under a
program supported by an arrangement under the IMF's Poverty
Reduction and Growth Facility."
</P>
<P>
The document adds that in response to the catastrophic
flooding that hit southern and central Mozambique earlier this
year, the World Bank and the IMF "decided to accelerate the debt
relief by forgiving 100 percent of the debt service owed by
Mozambique in the next 12 months, so that Mozambique will not have
to pay any debt service to either institution during this period".
</P>
<P>
Very few countries have so far qualified for either original
HIPC or enhanced HIPC. According to the World Bank, 36 countries
(29 of them in sub- Saharan Africa) are "expected to qualify" for
enhanced HIPC.
</P>
<P>
But so far only six countries have reached the completion point
of the original initiative (Mozambique, Uganda, Bolivia,
Mauritania, Tanzania, and Guyana), as the Bretton Woods
institutions demand that countries applying for HIPC must
demonstrate a "satisfactory track record" for perhaps as much as
three years first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0054 </DOCNO>
