<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toronto Stock Exchange Sees Another Tumbling Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- In abreast with Wall Street,
Canada's benchmark index saw a third tumbling day in a row
Wednesday, with one of the country's brightest tech stars plunging
to Earth.
</P>
<P>
The Toronto Stock Exchange 300 composite index (TSE 300) closed
310.36 points or 3.32 percent lower at 9,047.67, losing nearly all
its surprise gains for the past month.
</P>
<P>
Up to 172.64 million shares worth 4.82 billion Canadian dollars
(about 3.30 billion U.S. dollars) changed hands at the TSE, where
decliners beat advancers 702 to 496 with another 225 issues
closing flat.
</P>
<P>
TSE 300 was downed due to the on-going heavy technology-focused
selloff, which cost Research in Motion Ltd. (RIM) 3.6 billion
Canadian dollars (about 2.5 billion U.S. dollars) in its market
value.
</P>
<P>
The Ontario-based world star in wireless pagers saw its shares
fall 52.65 dollars (about 36.01 U.S. dollars) to close at 68
dollars (about 46.51 U.S. dollars) after the company reported
revenue growth in the current quarter would be flat.
</P>
<P>
RIM shares traded at 260 dollars (about 177.84 U.S. dollars)
this year after ranking as the second best performer in Canada's
benchmark index in 1999.
</P>
<P>
There was also heavy selling in telecommunications equipment
maker Nortel Networks Corp., telecom giant BCE Inc. and a slew of
other Canadian tech companies.
</P>
<P>
Blue-chip heavyweights Nortel and BCE, which sank 10 percent
and 9 percent respectively, dragged the market lower in concert
with the tech-laden Nasdaq composite index, which closed 286.26
points, or 7 percent lower, at 3,769.64.
</P>
<P>
Skittish investors were concerned that they might have
overrated the high-flying technology sector, which would not be
able to meet expectations during this corporate earnings period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wholesale Prices Surge 1 Percent in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. wholesale prices shot up
1 percent in March, led by the biggest jump in energy costs in
nearly 10 years, the Labor Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The advance in the Producer Price Index, which measures
inflation pressures before they reach the consumer, came from a
huge 5.8 percent gain in energy prices, the sharpest rise since a
7.5 percent increase posted in October 1990.
</P>
<P>
Excluding volatile energy and food categories, the "core" rate
of inflation at the wholesale level rose a tiny 0.1 percent, right
on target with many analysts' predictions, suggesting that most
other prices were well behaved.
</P>
<P>
In February, wholesale prices also surged 1 percent, which
marked the largest gain in nearly 10 years, while the core rate
rose an expected 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, wholesale prices have been rising at an
annual rate of 8.2 percent, compared with a 3 percent gain for all
of 1999. The pickup in this year's wholesale prices largely
reflects rising energy costs.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report, the Commerce Department said that retail
sales rose a bigger-than-expected 0.4 percent in March, but were
less brisk than the month before. But excluding the volatile
category of cars sales, March's total retail sales were up a
strong 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
And in a third report, the Labor Department said the number of
Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits last week
rose by 3,000 to 264,000, but still left claims in a range
suggesting that companies are scrambling to find qualified workers.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates five times since
June 30 to slow the speeding economy and to keep inflation from
escalating. Given the outlook for strong continuing growth, many
analysts expect the Fed will boost rates again on May 16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
