<HEADLINE> Security Alert in N.Irish Police Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Security forces in Northern
Ireland Thursday sealed off an area near the border following the
discovery of a suspicious object near a police station.
</P>
<P>
The cylindrical object was in a car parked near the police
station in Roslea, County Fermanagh, the west of the province.
</P>
<P>
The discovery followed an earlier report of a muffled explosion
shortly before midnight Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said a Volvo 340 hatchback was found with
all its windows blown out about 400 meters from the police station.
</P>
<P>
The vehicle was discovered near a house under construction at
approximately 0810 BST Thursday morning by a farmer.
</P>
<P>
He said four houses had been evacuated due to the discovery.
</P>
<P>
Queen Elizabeth visited Hillsborough, just south of Belfast,
Wednesday on a trip that had sparked concern about possible
attacks by republican splinter groups.
</P>
<P>
She was making a rare visit to present a gallantry award to the
Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC), the province's police force.
</P>
<P>
Security was tight but there were fears that republican
dissidents might stage attacks on security forces elsewhere in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's main extremist groups, including the Irish
Republican Army (IRA), are on ceasefire after 30 years of conflict
about the future of British rule.
</P>
<P>
But republican hardliners have launched sporadic attacks in a
bid to wreck a peace accord that they say cements London's
sovereignty over the disputed region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
