<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Doctors "Allow" Elderly to Die </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Doctors in Britain were accused of
allowing elderly patients to die by deciding not to make attempts
to revive them should they fall unconscious as a result of serious
illness in hospital.
</P>
<P>
The Age Concern organization said Thursday doctors were
increasingly ignoring the wishes of patients -- and sometimes not
even asking patients -- when it comes to making resuscitation
decisions, the BBC reported.
</P>
<P>
British Medical Association guidelines state that patients or
their relatives should be consulted about any decision not to
resuscitate.
</P>
<P>
The BMA admits that some junior doctors may be too nervous to
involve patients and their relatives in discussions about whether
to revive or not.
</P>
<P>
Age Concern was calling for a full inquiry into the treatment
of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the case was highlighted of a cancer patient who
discovered that had she fallen unconscious in hospital, doctors
would have made no efforts to resuscitate her.
</P>
<P>
Jill Baker only found out after she left hospital that the
comment "inappropriate for resuscitation" had been written on her
notes.
</P>
<P>
Neither she nor her husband had been approached or asked for
their views on the subject.
</P>
<P>
Despite being "written off" by a doctor who had not even met
her, nine months later she is alive and enjoying life.
</P>
<P>
Campaigners said the case highlighted the way doctors were
flouting guidance on so-called "end of life" issues and making
decisions without the permission of patients.
</P>
<P>
Mrs Baker, 67, from Portsmouth, who has stomach cancer, was
admitted to a ward in the city's St Mary's Hospital last July
after a tube used in her chemotherapy treatment became infected
and she developed septicemia.
</P>
<P>
She eventually discharged herself because she was unhappy with
her care and demanded to see her hospital notes.
</P>
<P>
A doctor had written on top of the records, "In view of the
underlying diagnosis (cancer), in the event of cardiac arrest or
stroke, resuscitation would be inappropriate."
</P>
<P>
The note also said "Do not ring 555" -- the hospital number for
the resuscitation team.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for St Mary's Hospital said, "The hospital has
admitted that the Do Not Resuscitate message was put on Mrs Baker'
s notes inappropriately.
</P>
<P>
"The doctor involved was formally seen by the medical director
but no longer works for the hospital." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
