<HEADLINE> Putin, OSCE Head Discuss Chechnya, Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President-elect Vladimir
Putin met Thursday with Benita Ferrero-Waldner, head of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), and
the two discussed Chechnya and investment in Russia.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting in the Kremlin, Putin told Ferrero-Waldner
that the OSCE is the main European security system and that OSCE
activities should be strengthened not only in former Soviet
republics but also elsewhere like Kosovo, said Sergei Prikhodko,
deputy head of the Russian presidential staff.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Ferrero-Waldner, who also serves as foreign
minister of Austria, Putin set forth Russia's overall economic
strategy and its plans to improve the investment environment in
the country, the Interfax news agency quoted Prikhodko as saying.
</P>
<P>
Putin also briefed Ferrero-Waldner on Russian efforts to settle
the conflict in Chechnya, where federal authorities are trying to
restore government and the economy.
</P>
<P>
Ferrero-Waldner welcomed the institution in Russia of an office
of presidential human rights commissioner for Chechnya, and said
the OSCE will cooperate with the office.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian foreign minister, who arrived here Thursday, met
earlier with her Russian counterpart, Igor Ivanov, and the two
discussed bilateral ties and signed a protocol on avoidance of
double taxation.
</P>
<P>
Ferrero-Waldner is scheduled to leave Moscow and head for the
North Caucasus later Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
