<HEADLINE> Belgian King's Heart Operation Successful: Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Belgian King Albert II underwent
an emergency heart operation early Thursday and the quadruple
bypass operation turned out to be successful, according to
hospital sources.
</P>
<P>
The operation took two and a half hours in the early morning
after the king was hospitalized on Wednesday night after feeling
chest pains that were diagnosed as having been caused by the
narrowing of the blood vessels in the heart.
</P>
<P>
The operation was conducted by Doctor Hugo van Ermen at
Brussels's Onze Lieve Vrouw d'Alost Hospital.
</P>
<P>
King Albert II woke up in the morning with no signs of
complication and he was breathing normally, hospital sources
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
He has spoken to Queen Paola and will remain in intensive care
for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian royal palace announced later in the day that the
king would have to rest for several weeks before resuming
exercising royal functions.
</P>
<P>
The king and Queen Paola were scheduled to receive the visiting
Jordanian king on Wednesday, but only the queen and Prince Laurent
received the visitor and his family instead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
