<HEADLINE> Leeds United Shocked at UEFA Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- English premier league soccer club
Leeds United have been charged for failing to control their
players during the controversial first leg of the UEFA Cup semi-
final against Galatasaray.
</P>
<P>
UEFA brought the charges after four Leeds players were booked
in the first leg, which the Turkish side won 2-0. The West
Yorkshire club said it was astounded at the decision.
</P>
<P>
Leeds United secretary Ian Silvester said: "I was astounded to
receive this notification from UEFA. But apparently there is a
rule you can be charged with failing to control your players if
more than three are booked in the same game."
</P>
<P>
"The matter will be dealt with at a disciplinary meeting on 27
April," he said.
</P>
<P>
But European football's ruling body is still silent on what
action they will take over the murders of Leeds fans Chris Loftus
and Kevin Speight during violence in Istanbul on the eve of the
match last week.
</P>
<P>
UEFA will announce on Friday whether Galatasaray fans will be
allowed into Elland Road for the second leg after Leeds called for
them to be banned.
</P>
<P>
UEFA president Lennart Johansson has already suggested that a
limited number of Galatasaray supporters will be allowed to attend.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is very likely the match will go ahead at Elland
Road and that a restricted number of Galatasaray fans will be
allowed in," he said. "This has to be agreed by the (UEFA)
committee of course, and things could change." 
</P>
</TEXT>
