<HEADLINE> Diplomatic News Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The accountability review results provided by the United States
concerning the U.S. bombing of the Chinese embassy in the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia last May are not tenable and the Chinese
side found them unacceptable, said Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Sun Yuxi here.
</P>
<P>
At a regular press conference, Sun said the U.S. bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia on May 8, last year, was an
extremely serious international unlawful act which infringed
gravely on China's sovereignty, greatly hurt the dignity of the
Chinese people and severely damaged Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Gabonese Minister to Visit China
</P>
<P>
Jean Ping, Minister of State and Minister of Foreign Affairs,
Cooperation and French Countries of the Gabon Republic, will pay
an official visit to China between April 20 and 26 at the
invitation of Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, Chinese
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Sun Yuxi announced here.
</P>
<P>
China Expresses Strong Resentment, Regret
</P>
<P>
 over Dalai Lama's Japan Trip
</P>
<P>
China today expressed "strong resentment and regret" over Japan
allowing the Dalai Lama into the country, in disregard of repeated
representations made by the Chinese side.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question at a regular press conference,
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi said, the Dalai Lama
is definitely not merely an ordinary religious figure but a
political exile who has long been engaged in activities to split
China under the cloak of religion.
</P>
<P>
China demands that Japan honor its commitment in acknowledging
that the Tibet issue is an internal affair of China, be as good as
its words, so as to safeguard the overall Sino-Japanese relations,
Sun said.
</P>
<P>
 Dialogue Is Only Correct Way in Resolving
</P>
<P>
Differences on Human Rights Issue: FM Spokesman
</P>
<P>
Dialogue based on equality and mutual respect is the only
correct way in resolving differences among countries on the issue
of human rights while confrontation leads to nowhere, China's
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Sun Yuxi said here.
</P>
<P>
Responding to reporters at a regular press conference, Sun said
that China has taken note of the decision made by the European
Union that it would not co-sponsor an anti-China resolution tabled
by the United States at the current session on human rights in
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
"We have all along believed that the dialogue based on equality
and mutual respect is the only correct way in resolving
differences among countries on the issue of human rights while
confrontation leads to nowhere," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
 Lee Teng-hui's Activities have Political Intentions
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Sun Yuxi pointed out that
Lee Teng-hui's activities abroad, in whatever ways, names and
capacities, have obvious political intentions.
</P>
<P>
"So we hope that countries concerned, including Japan, will
stick to the one-China policy, honor their promises, and handle
such issues properly," Sun said at a regular press conference when
asked to comment on Lee's possible trip to Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
