<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Student Studies Amphibians on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- In a first ever e-mail
multinational study, a Canadian doctoral student mobilized about
200 researchers to find that the world's amphibian population has
most likely decreased by more than 50 percent since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
Heff Houlahan, 40, a doctoral student of biology at the
University of Ottawa, and his multinational team concluded that
the amphibian population declined at the steepest rate of 15
percent in the 1960s, the country's Ottawa Citizen reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The shrinkage continued, but at a slower rate of 2 percent
respectively in the 1980s and the 1990s, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The team compiled scientific data of the last four decades from
close to 1,000 studies. Up to 157 species of frogs and salamanders
were involved in the three-year-long multinational e-project.
</P>
<P>
This was unlike a traditional study that relied on original
laboratory research, the newspaper said, adding that Houlahan met
only one of his collaborators face-to-face over the course of the
project.
</P>
<P>
Houlahan was quoted as saying that the next phase in the
project is to study the cause of the decline of amphibian
population.
</P>
<P>
Scientists suspect the loss of habitat, the impact of
fertilizers and pesticides and the thinning ozone layer will
continue to be challenges to the survival of amphibians.
</P>
<P>
"My feeling is this is just one more indicator of the fact that
we are overworking the planet," he said in reference to his next
step of 18 months in the research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
