<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Pledges Probe in Human Rights Violations in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President-elect Vladimir
Putin said here Thursday that all alleged human rights violations
in the breakaway republic of Chechnya will be investigated and
those responsible will be severely punished.
</P>
<P>
"All cases of human rights violations and abuse in the anti-
terrorist campaign in the Northern Caucasus, no matter who is
responsible for them, are being thoroughly investigated," Putin
said in a statement released by the Kremlin press service.
</P>
<P>
"The punishment will be severe if guilt is proven," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has been under mounting pressure from the West on
alleged human rights abuses in Chechnya, where federal troops are
fighting rebels in a campaign launched last September.
</P>
<P>
The assaults on the rebels came after waves of armed Chechen
incursions into neighboring Dagestan and a series of apartment
bombings that killed over 300 people in Moscow and two other
cities. Chechen militants were blamed for the blasts.
</P>
<P>
"The problem of responsibility of violators of human rights and
lawfulness in Chechnya are permanently in the center of attention"
of the Russian leadership, Putin said.
</P>
<P>
"Several cases have been opened on charges of genocide,
abduction, inter-religious and inter-ethnic discord, among them
the murder of 33 residents of the Mekenskaya village of the
Naurskaya district and 10 Russian-speaking residents of the
Chervlennaya village of the Shelkovskaya district," the Interfax
news agency quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Putin also pointed to the massive rights abuses by
Chechen militants in the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
He said that Dzhokhar Dudayev, the former ruler of Chechnya,
turned the republic into "a criminal and terrorist enclave
dominated by arbitrariness, lawlessness and neglect of elementary
human rights."
</P>
<P>
"National and regional discrimination, hostage-taking, slavery
and slave trade, murder, rape and public execution were everyday
life affairs in the republic. The bandits profaned fundamental
principles of Islam and waged a war against the whole population
of Chechnya under the cover of Sharia norms. About 220,000
Russians and 650,000 Chechens have had to flee the republic since
1992," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The restoration of law and respect for human rights on the
territory of the republic is a priority of Russia's state policy,"
Putin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
