<HEADLINE> China to Ensure Traffic Safety for Pupils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China is urging school-age
children to wear eye-catching yellow caps in an effort to reduce
traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, where the practice was introduced in 1996, traffic
accidents involving school-age children have been brought under
control as no school-age children wearing the bright caps died
from traffic accidents over the past two years in the municipality,
police said today.
</P>
<P>
Donning high-visibility hats is just one feature of the "
Youngsters Return Home Safely" campaign which began this month in
36 major Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
The program also recommends that school-age children go to and
from school in groups, and that some of them should carry signs
while crossing streets so that drivers will be sure to see them.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was jointly sponsored by the Chinese Communist
Youth League Central Committee, the Ministry of Education, and the
Ministry of Public Security, in response to a speech by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin calling on society to provide a safe
environment for school-age children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
