<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 211 Chinese Died from Major Traffic Accidents in First Quarter (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- In the first quarter of the year,
a total of 211 Chinese died and another 211 injured in 13 major
traffic accidents, each of which claimed at least ten lives, the
Ministry of Public Security said today.
</P>
<P>
The number of major traffic accidents, deaths and injured
people is 38 percent, 38 percent and 46 percent down from the
corresponding period of last year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Two of the 13 accidents occurred in central China's Hunan
Province, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The biggest traffic accident happened in east China's Fujian
Province on January 1 of the year.
</P>
<P>
Owing to poor visibility at night, a passenger vehicle with 51
people on board collided with a cargo vehicle running in front of
it, killing 22 people and wounding 29.
</P>
<P>
Meng Hongwei, director of the Traffic Management Bureau of the
Ministry of Public Security, said that compared with the same
period of last year, traffic accidents for long-distance passenger
and cargo vehicles have shrunk in the first quarter of the year,
thanks for the tightened control by traffic management departments,
while short-distance passenger and cargo vehicles have witnessed
more traffic accidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Raises College Enrollment Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China's colleges and universities
will enroll 1.8 million freshmen this autumn term, an increase of
200,000 over last year's total, an official with the Ministry of
Education said here today.
</P>
<P>
Qu Zhenyuan, the director of the ministry's student department,
also disclosed that universities will enroll more students from
the country's western area in line with the central government's
plan to develop the vast, backward region.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will also enroll 120,000 graduate students this
year, 95,000 of whom will pursue master's degrees.
</P>
<P>
He said that the age limit for undergraduates has been upped to
25. Over 49 percent of the national college entrance examination
participants will be enrolled this year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will offer preferential policies relating to the
entrance exams for students from the west who are willing to work
in west after graduation.
</P>
<P>
Over half of China's universities will use on-line enrollment
this year, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
