<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Omani Minister of Petroleum and Natural Gas Mohammed
al-Ramhi said his country has resumed its previous oil production
level fixed at 900,000 barrels per day (bpd) under the agreement
reached by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)
last month.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian economic daily Al Alam El-Yom on Thursday quoted
al-Ramhi as saying his country plans to increase production to one
million bpd with collaboration of the foreign oil companies working
in the country, which has currently 5.6 billion barrels of oil
reserves.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Visa International Company said in a statement that the
Saudi credit card market accounts for 60 percent of the total of 3.
45 million visa cards issued in the six Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
Al Alam El-Yom on Thursday quoted the statement as saying that
Saudi Arabia has issued, until the end of last year, 1.39 million
cards, followed by the United Arab Emirates that issued 886,000
cards and Kuwait, 835,000 cards.
</P>
<P>
The total spending through the use of visa credit cards in the
region amounted to 19.98 billion U.S. dollars, with Saudi Arabia
ranking first with 8.65 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement said these figures are not final.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabian Oil Company "Aramco" said it is
currently exporting about 40 percent of crude oil and its
derivatives to the world markets via the port of Yanbu industrial
city, west of the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
According to Al Alam El-Yom, the company said the oil pipeline
has a transport capacity of 5 million bpd, while the daily capacity
of gas pipelines reaches 280,000 barrels of liquefied natural gas.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's Is Bank and Telecom Italia Wednesday
purchased the first of two new mobile phone GSM network licenses
with a record high bid of 2.25 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The group's unexpected high offer beat by far that of its
closest rival, a Sabanci-led consortium, including Dogan Holding,
Dogus Holding and Spanish Telefonica, which offered 1.35 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Sabanci-led consortium said that it would bid for the second
license, which will be awarded through a bidding war based on the
price of the first license.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- As Iran begins to block ships smuggling Iraqi fuel oil
in the Persian Gulf, Turkish experts believe that fuel oil entering
Turkey from Iraq across the Iraqi-Turkish border will increase,
reported Turkish Daily News on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
By differentiating between crude oil and fuel oil coming from
Iraq, oil experts prefer crude oil to fuel oil from Iraq as Turkey
has five refineries to produce enough fuel oil for the country's
market.
</P>
<P>
The government takes 300 percent tax on fuel from Iraq, but it
has failed to block the fuel oil trade at the border.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's ready-to-wear sector has started a series of
activities to expand its export market in targeted countries,
reported the Anatolia News Agency on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mete Oguz, chairman of the Aegean Ready-to-Wear Exporters Union,
said Wednesday that they are working to increase their export to
Denmark, Spain and Britain.
</P>
<P>
A delegation composed of 23 members from 16 companies held
bilateral meetings with 100 Turkish firms last week in Izmir,
southwest Turkey. They will come back to Izmir in two or three
months to give orders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
