<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Government Lifts Ban on Golan Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli government on
Thursday lifted a ban on construction on the Golan Heights, a move
that might harm the Israeli-Syrian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Yossi Kucik, a confidant of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and director general of his office, announced Thursday that all
construction and development plans on the Golan will be given the
go-ahead from now on.
</P>
<P>
The strategic plateau was occupied by Israel in the 1967 Middle
East War.
</P>
<P>
The lifting of the ban might pave the way for the implementation
of a large tourism project at Hamat Gader, another disputed area
along the border between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The Golan Jewish settlements leaders have welcomed the lifting
of the ban, saying it will not only release land for the
construction of housing units but will also encourage economic
development in the area.
</P>
<P>
Kucik's announcement ended the freeze order issued by Barak last
year, when he was elected as prime minister and made peace with
Syria a top priority of his administration.
</P>
<P>
Barak reportedly thought the ban, as a good-will gesture, will
convince Syrian President Hafez al-Assad of Israel's sincerity for
peace, as the return of the Golan is the major topic in the
Israeli-Syrian peace track.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the reason behind the lifting of the ban, according to
Israel Radio reports, is Barak's deep disappointment toward the
stalled peace negotiations with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts even claimed that such a decision has finally
slammed the door for talks with Syria and begun to restore the
business on the plateau "as usual".
</P>
<P>
The off-again, on-again talks between Israel and Syria resumed
last December after a 45-month break, but only to break off again
in January after two rounds of talks.
</P>
<P>
The latest effort to revive the talks, a summit meeting between
Assad and U.S. President Bill Clinton in Geneva on March 26, failed
to make progress as expected.
</P>
<P>
During Barak's meeting with Clinton in Washington Tuesday, the
Syrian peace track occupied little time, according to a senior
official in Barak's office.
</P>
<P>
The official also said that both leaders thought the
possibilities for new developments are very slim, although "the
door on the Syrian track is not closed" yet.
</P>
<P>
In such a context, Israeli Minister in Prime Minister's Office
Haim Ramon Tuesday confirmed that the construction of 200 more home
units had broken ground in Katzrin, the largest Jewish settlement
on the Golan Heights with 6,700 settlers.
</P>
<P>
Ramon said that because the peace with Syria are apparently not
in the offing, he thought the way should be cleared for the "
natural growth" for settlements on the Golan.
</P>
<P>
There are about 17,000 Jewish settlers living in the Golan
Heights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: 57 Killed, 100 Missing in Philippine Ship Mishap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- At least 57 people died and 100
others are missing when a cargo vessel capsized Wednesday night
off Sulu Province in the southern Philippines, the authorities
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Orlando Mercado of the Department of National Defense
said ferry Arlahada capsized at about 20:30 (12:30 GMT) Wednesday
off Jolo, Sulu Province, killing at least 57 people.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 others are still missing and feared dead, said
Mercado, who also heads the National Disaster Coordinating Council.
</P>
<P>
Local TV reports said some 79 passengers were rescued and
brought to local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Maritime Police command in Western Mindanao
said Arlahada was on its way to Tawi-Tawi Province after which it
was scheduled to go to Sabah, Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The authorities estimated that the ship was carrying more than
200 passengers when it was actually fit for only 50.
</P>
<P>
Coast guard officials from Jolo town said Arlahada left the
port of Jolo after it was checked by their men at around 18:00 (10:
00 GMT) with only 20 passengers on board.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that the vessel picked up many passengers along
the way by stopping at sea while motorized pump-boats side-docked
to bring in passengers.
</P>
<P>
Survivors of the sea tragedy recounted that the ship leaned on
its side at around 20:00 (12:00 GMT) but the crew were not able to
bring it back to its original sailing position, prompting sea
waters to run into all the cabins an other parts of the vessel.
</P>
<P>
Sulu Governor Abdusakur Tan said Arlahada with its main port of
call in Zamboanga city was illegally carrying passengers over its
capacity when it sank more than two hours after it left Jolo port.
</P>
<P>
Coast guard officials also said the vessel capsized due to
overloading of passengers and it should not have carried
passengers as it was licensed as a cargo vessel.
</P>
<P>
According to Tan, search and rescue operations were immediately
launched by a combined team of the Philippine Navy, the Philippine
Coast Guard and the Maritime Police after the tragedy. He said
rescue teams are still continuing their search and rescue
operations.
</P>
<P>
However, Tan feared that most of the passengers of the ill-
fated vessel have either been drowned or were devoured by big
fishes in the sea.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Mercado said in a radio interview that the
government has mobilized concerned agencies to extend all possible
assistance to the victims.
</P>
<P>
He said his office is coordinating with the Department of
Transportation and Communication on the matter.
</P>
<P>
"We have been working in tandem with the governor of Sulu,
Abdusakur Tan, and other government agencies," Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the authorities are still verifying the
overloading issue and that most of the passengers were not listed
on the vessel's manifesto.
</P>
<P>
Mercado also expressed fear that the coming observance of the
Holy Week will prompt ship operators to overload commercial sea
vessels in coming days.
</P>
<P>
"This practice is obviously rampant. What's more alarming is
that the rule and regulations regarding overloading are being
ignored all over the country," Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
Of all the sea disasters in the Philippines, the most
unforgettable would perhaps be the collision between the passenger
ship Dona Paz and the oil tanker Vector in 1987.
</P>
<P>
Dona Paz was ferrying passengers who were then going home for
Christmas. It was supposed to carry only 1,800 passengers but
unofficial estimates put the number of the dead at about 3,000 in
the incident.
</P>
<P>
Only 24 people survived, prompting historians to dub the mishap
as the "worst maritime disaster of the century." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
