<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Opposition Hold General Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Thursday witnessed
another countrywide general strike called by the Bangladesh
Nationalist Party(BNP)-led opposition alliance as part of the
opposition's long-drawn anti-government campaign.
</P>
<P>
Security was tightened in Dhaka as the opposition called the
dawn-to-dusk general strike but there were no reports of major
violence despite sporadic incidents of bomb blasts and street
marches.
</P>
<P>
The public transport system remained in operation, though fewer
buses were seen than usual, and private cars were off the streets
in some areas of the capital. Shops, major markets and schools and
other academic institutions were closed but offices, including
financial institutions, were open.
</P>
<P>
According to the railway department, there were no reports of
disruption of train services from anywhere while civil aviation
sources said other than two domestic flights, all flights in local
and international routes operated as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The last time the opposition enforced such a countrywide
shutdown was on February 28 to press their demand for the
resignation of the government and announcement of an early general
election, which is not scheduled before 2001.
</P>
<P>
According to newspaper reports, at least 30 persons were killed
and thousands injured in violence during the opposition's general
strikes in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling Awami League and its front organizations
Thursday held anti-general strike demonstrations in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Awami League supporters marched through city
streets to protest against the strike enforced by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
According to Awami League sources, the ruling party also held
similar processions in other cities.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance has recently started to discuss the
formation of an electoral alliance to contest the upcoming general
election. Its components have already begun preparing individually
for the election while carrying out the anti-government movement.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star reported Thursday that some senior leaders of
BNP, Jatiya Party (National Party), Jamaat-e-Islami and Islami
Oikya Jote (Islami Solidarity Front), which form the alliance,
told the daily that the parties have reached a consensus on
contesting the election together to fight the ruling Awami League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
