<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Sees Good Economic Conditions in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and an
International Monetary Fund (IMF) mission agreed Thursday that
favorable economic conditions have taken place in the Philippines
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of the Philippines and the visiting IMF
mission said in a joint press statement that the country's economy
is recovering on the strength of rapid export growth and a
recovery in domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Along with this, inflation has been lower than what was
programmed,helped by declining food prices. Similarly, the
external current account is in large surplus and official reserves
are at a comfortable level.
</P>
<P>
Both panels agreed that the solid economic fundamentals,
prudent implementation of the fiscal and monetary programs and
vigorous implementation of the government's reform agenda should
ensure a strong economic performance this year.
</P>
<P>
Real GDP growth is expected to be well within the government's
target range of 4 to 5 percent in 2000, reflecting the strong
recovery in industry and services as well.
</P>
<P>
The strong economic recovery was contributed by an improvement
in industry and services as well as a sustained growth of
agriculture.Inflation is expected to be between 5 and 6 percent
for this year, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF mission completed late Tuesday its fifth review of the
country's economy to release more funds for the country under its
1.4-billion U.S. dollar standby facility with the Philippine
government.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has so far disbursed 740 million dollars from the
standby fund and has extended the two-year program to June to
allow the release of the remaining funds. The IMF standby program
was originally due to expire in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
