<HEADLINE> Sweden Predicts 3.8 Percent GDP Growth for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish government Tuesday
revised its economic growth projection for this year to 3.8
percent from last autumn's 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the budget bill for spring put before the parliament, the
government predicts that export will grow by 7.6 percent in 2000,
2.4 percent higher than the growth rate of last year; and
household consumption will grow by 5 percent, 1 percent higher
than that of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the higher growth forecast has resulted from
the economic recovery in Sweden's major trading partners.
</P>
<P>
The minority Social Democrat government also plans to cut
public expenditures by 0.7 percent, which could help bring about a
budget surplus of 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Inflation would be 1.4 percent this year and unemployment would
be lowered to 4.6 percent, from 5.6 percent of last year.
</P>
<P>
As for the economy in 2001 to 2002, the government predicts a
growth between 2.0 and 2.9 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
