<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Pudong New Area (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Editor's note: This year is the
tenth anniversary of China's opening up and development of the
Pudong New Area in eastern Shanghai. To help readers have a better
understanding of Pudong, Xinhua will release a series of
backgrounders beginning today. The following is the first.
</P>
<P>
On April 18, 1990, the Chinese government declared the opening-
up and development of Pudong in a drive to rejuvenate Shanghai's
status as an international financial and trade center, and turn
Shanghai into a locomotive to promote economic development of the
Yangtze River valley.
</P>
<P>
After 10 years of joint efforts by the central and local
governments, who offered favorable policies, the 522-square-
kilometer Pudong, on the eastern bank of the Huangpu River which
cuts Shanghai into two parts, has become one of the most
attractive foreign investment zones in the country.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, 5,942 overseas companies were
operating in Pudong. These overseas-funded firms involve a total
investment of 29.44 billion U.S. dollars, including contractual
overseas investment amounting to 11.57 billion U.S. dollars. About
100 of the world's 500 leading multinationals are among the
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the leading overseas investor in Pudong
area last year with 266 million U.S. dollars of investment,
followed by Japan with 134 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, 5,183 Chinese companies flocked to Pudong
with a total registered capital of 19.4 billion yuan (about 2.34
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Businesses in the Pudong New Area are mainly engaged in
automobiles, information technology, iron and steel, household
appliances, petrochemicals, and pharmaceuticals. Pudong's products
are now sold to more than 130 countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Pudong New Area (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pudong is also a hot spot for bankers. Recent official
statistics show that 42 overseas banks have opened subsidiaries in
the area, with combined assets of 13.31 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some big names there are CitiBank, Standard Chartered Bank, and
Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation Limited.
</P>
<P>
Apart from foreign currency transactions, 24 of the overseas-
funded banks have been approved to engage in yuan business.
</P>
<P>
Pudong is composed of four parts: Lujiazui Financial and Trade
Zone, Jinqiao Exports Processing Zone, Waigaoqiao Bonded Zone, and
Zhangjiang High-Tech Park, with a population of 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
Pudong reported a gross domestic product of 80 billion yuan (
about 964 million U.S. dollars) in 1999, compared with 600 million
yuan a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
During the past decade, China has invested billions of dollars
in infrastructure construction, including bridges, expressways,
deep-water berths, telecommunications facilities, power plants,
water supply and drainage projects, and an international airport,
to develop Pudong.
</P>
<P>
The area, which was ignored for centuries, has changed
completely. Shanty towns are disappearing and nearly 200
skyscrapers, including China's tallest building, the Jinmao Tower,
are now part of the landscape.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
