<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Aircraft Producer Delivers Boeing Tail Part </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
CHENGDU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- An airplane manufacturer in
Chengdu, capital of southwest China's Sichuan Province, today
delivered a No.48 session, one of the Boeing tail parts, to
American Northrop Grumman Corporation (NG), based on a subcontract
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the Chengdu Aero Industrial Corporation signed an
agreement with NG to produce tail parts for the Boeing 757-200,
involving vertical tails, horizontal tails, and the No.48 sessions.
</P>
<P>
Industry insiders here note that the No.48 session is the
hardest of all tail parts to make, and the Chengdu company first
successfully fulfilled this task when it delivered a vertical tail
and horizontal tail in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to Boeing experts, the Boeing 757 aircraft, with two
engines and a single aisle, has the lowest seat-mile costs.
</P>
<P>
Boeing began its cooperation with China in the 1970s, and key
parts fitted in 3,100 Boeing planes now in service around the
world were produced in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
