<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Russia to Boost Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Russia Thursday
signed here a bilateral agreement to boost their economic
cooperation, trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by Malaysian International Trade and
Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz and Russian Trade Minister Mikhail
Fradkov.
</P>
<P>
The agreement paves the way for both countries to encourage and
promote mutually beneficial economic cooperation and render
assistance to private sectors to establish joint ventures in both
countries.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said it is also possible to counter-trade Russian space
technology which Malaysia is interested in for Malaysian palm oil
or rubber.
</P>
<P>
"Russia would like to have counter trade with Malaysia to
exchange its space technology and expertise for our products like
palm oil or rubber and negotiations are being undertaken with the
Primary Industries Ministry," Rafidah told reporters after the
signing of the agreement here.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said the agreement focused on industry, investment,
aviation, shipbuilding, communication and multimedia, space
technology, electronic, metallurgy, medicine, agriculture and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
She said both parties shall render assistance for the
development of economic cooperation and promote participation of
the private sector in construction, modernization and
reconstruction of enterprises in both countries.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Russia currently have a very good trade
relationship with total trade standing at 358.7 million U.S.
dollars last year, which was 0.2 percent of Malaysia's global
trade.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has submitted its draft of Investment Guarantee
Agreement to Russia and would be awaiting their decision, Rafidah
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
