<HEADLINE> Australian PM Sets Tone for Liberal Party Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard set the tone for the ruling Liberal Party national
conference Thursday night with a plea for the corporate community
to do more to help those in need.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which starts Friday in Melbourne in Southeast
Australia, will focus on the government's social policies,
especially Howard's push for mutual obligation and a new social
coalition in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Howard, who will deliver two keynote speeches at the conference,
Thursday night launched a CARE Australia corporate roundtable,
where business leaders have offered support for the work of the
international aid agency.
</P>
<P>
He said CARE's initiative was a perfect example of how business
could become more involved in philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
"In launching the corporate council, I'm associating myself
very enthusiastically with the notion of what I've called the
social coalition," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
"That is based on a belief that the goals we want to achieve in
our community can't be achieved by the individual sectors of our
community operating in isolation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The business community and its prosperity and its wealth is
vital to the economic growth of our nation and the employment of
its people," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Liberals will also use the conference to help raise funds
for the next election, with business delegates paying 5,000
Australian dollars (3,100 U.S. dollars) a head to listen to the
debates and to receive policy briefings from senior ministers.
</P>
<P>
The Liberals reportedly want the convention to be a showcase of
unity after a recent party split over mandatory sentencing laws in
some parts of Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
