<HEADLINE> Asian Recovery to Boost Australia's Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Asian economic recovery
would increase arrivals from the region to Australia by more than
13 percent this year, Australian Tourist Commission Deputy
Managing Director Bill Calderwood said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Calderwood said that after two "tough years" in Asia, his
commission is ready to capitalize on the region's economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian markets are almost back to their pre-economic crisis
levels," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Calderwood said exceptional growth last year from key markets
such as Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand and China combined to
deliver a total Asian growth of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Arrivals from Asia are forecast to grow a further 13.4 percent
this year to around 1.3 million and the opportunities for
Australia in Asia have never been greater," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics has said that while Asian
arrivals grew 11 percent in 1999, Asian travelers' expenditure
went up by 14 percent during the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
