<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fighting Drought in Northern Area to Ensure Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China is tackling the drought in
the north in the current spring ploughing season to ensure this
year's harvest.
</P>
<P>
Northern China has been hit by drought, especially the vast
land along the Yellow and Huaihe rivers, according to the State
Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the drought to the shortage of rainfall,
windy weather, and rising temperature since spring.
</P>
<P>
The April figure shows that 6.2 million hectares of farmland
crops have been affected by the drought, and some 13.8 million
people and 9.9 million domestic animals are reported to have a
shortage of drinking water.
</P>
<P>
Winter wheat is at a critical stage, and local governments in
the draught-hit regions are doing all they can to tackle the
problem.
</P>
<P>
Hebei Province has irrigated 1.76 million ha. of land,
involving some 2.6 million people, and Shanxi Province has decided
to allocate 360 million yuan to solve the water shortage.
</P>
<P>
Other provinces including Shangdong, northern Jiangsu, and
Shaanxi have all taken measures to tackle the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
