<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encourages Foreign Investment in Agriculture (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China will take a series of
measures to encourage foreign capital to flow into the country's
agriculture sector, an official of the State Development Planning
Commission (SDPC) said here today.
</P>
<P>
SDPC and related departments are revising foreign investment
regulations to give preferential treatment to foreign investment
in the agriculture sector, said Zhang Xiaoqiang, director of the
Commission's Foreign Capital Utilization Department, at the China
Agriculture Forum.
</P>
<P>
These policies include cutting import taxes, income taxes and
various fees, he said, adding that foreign capital may come in to
the sector in several forms such as joint ventures, solely owned
ventures, and owning of stock shares.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China has witnessed a surge of foreign capital
in its agriculture sector, and last year the contracted foreign
investment in the sector jumped 22 percent to 1.5 billion US
dollars despite the fact that total contracted foreign investment
dropped 21 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that foreign capital has played an important role in
the construction of agricultural infrastructure, the advancement
of agro-technology, and the restructure of the rural economy, and
has gained good economic returns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encourages Foreign Investment in Agriculture (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Experts attending the forum said that the demand for foreign
capital in the sector will increase with the further development
of agriculture, and that China's huge agriculture market will
created unprecedented opportunities for foreign investment after
the country joins the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
China will further improve the environment for foreign
investment and trade in agriculture and promote cooperation
between Chinese enterprises and their foreign counterparts, said
Wang Baorui, China's vice-minister of agriculture, at the opening
ceremony of the ongoing International Agro-Foodtech Expo, which
attracted over 300 agriculture-related companies from 17 countries.
</P>
<P>
While visiting the expo, Joyce Quin, minister of state of the
British Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, said that
China's agriculture market is large and important and Britain will
enhance cooperation with China in the areas from dairy, livestock,
and cereals to agro-research and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
"China's accession to the WTO will increase trade in both
directions and intensify cooperation between the UK and China,"
she said, adding that she expects more British companies will
invest in China.
</P>
<P>
Her views were shared by many foreign companies at the expo.
Sabine de Beaudrap, Asia Area Manager of the French Association
for the Development of International Exchanges of Food and
Agriculture Products and Technologies, said that French companies
take great interest in China's agriculture market, and that she
believes more business opportunities will arise when trade
barriers are lowered after China's entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiaoqiang noted that foreign investment in agriculture
will be decided by the market, and foreign companies can cooperate
with Chinese companies under all kinds of ownership, including
private enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
