<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Trade Shows Rapid Growth in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade in the
first quarter this year topped 98.2 billion U.S. dollars,
representing an impressive 40-percent growth from a year earlier,
and raking in a surplus of 5.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to figures in a report released by the General
Administration of Customs today, exports in the first three months
hit 51.7 billion dollars, up 39 percent year on year, and imports
reached 46.5 billion dollars, up 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
In March alone, total trade jumped 30 percent to 37.9 billion
dollars, with exports up 36 percent to 20.1 billion dollars and
imports up 24 percent to 17.8 billion dollars, leaving a surplus
of 2.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The sizable growth in foreign trade in the first quarter this
year was attributed to factors such as the general recovery in the
world economy, and the Chinese government's campaign to boost
trade.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the United States, Japan and the European Union
continued to yield good results. Russia, the Republic of Korea,
Hong Kong and Southeast Asian countries also contributed to
boosting China's exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
