<HEADLINE> China's Import Growth Slows Down in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China's imports maintained the
growth momentum in March in spite of a decline after the vigorous
surge in the previous two months this year, according to customs
figures released today.
</P>
<P>
Imports in March rose 24 percent over that of the same month
last year, but the growth rate fell far from the average 54
percent in January and February. The rate for the first three
months put together stood at 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
Total imports in the first quarter were 46.5 billion U.S.
dollars, of which processing trade imports took up 19.56 billion
dollars, up 35.5 percent year on year. Overseas-invested
businesses imported goods and facilities worth 2.6 billion U.S.
dollars as part of their investment, up 9.3 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
