<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Export Growth in First Quarterly High in Nearly Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The latest statistics from the
General Administration of Customs shows that China's exports in
the first three months this year rose by 39 percent over the same
period last year, registering the highest growth rate since the
second quarter of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the sharp rise to China's export decline in
the first quarter last year, the steady economic growth in the
United States and the European Union, the recovering of the Asian
economy, and a series of policies encouraging exports adopted by
the country last year.
</P>
<P>
During the first three months, non-processing exports displayed
high growth, and state-owned enterprises reported higher export
growth than that of overseas-invested companies.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China's exports to the united States,
Japan, and the European Union maintained rapid growth in the three
months at a rate of 34 percent, while exports to neighboring
countries and regions had a sharp rise of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The export of capital- and technology-intensive products also
rose rapidly, with that of labor-intensive products gaining a
growth momentum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
