<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Suggest Applying High-tech to Control Desert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have suggested
introducing high-tech methods to control the deteriorating
desertification of northwest China, which has caused several
severe dust storms this spring.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech should include biotechnology, chemistry and water-
saving technologies, said Shan Lun, an academician with the Soil
and Water Conservation Institute under the Chinese Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Shan, who has spent years studying soil conservation in western
China, said the sand-fixing methods developed by Chinese
scientists in their fight against the desert have been proved
effective.
</P>
<P>
Without the forest shelter belts covering over 30 million
hectares in northwest, north and northeast China, the dust storms
would have been even more violent, said Shan.
</P>
<P>
Since the trees planted in the last ten years are still young,
it will take eight to ten more before they play a full role, Shan
said.
</P>
<P>
A new chemical material which can absorb and release a large
quantity of water has been developed, and if the production costs
can be lowered, it can be used in agriculture and afforestation in
the western region, said Shan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, water-saving technologies should also be applied
in industries, agriculture, and people's daily lives, Shan added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
