<HEADLINE> HK's Building Quality Reform Plan Okayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Housing Authority of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) has formally
embarked on the road to construction reform with the endorsement
Thursday of a two-phase implementation plan containing 50
recommendations on ways to enhance building quality.
</P>
<P>
Rosanna Wong, chairman of the Housing Authority, said this is
an important step forward in translating the authority's
determination into action.
</P>
<P>
Addressing immediate public concerns, Phase One of the reform
covers areas vital to customer and building safety and will
provide a conducive foundation for the execution of subsequent
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
Some of these measures have already kicked off and the
remainder will commence immediately, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
Phase Two of the package, which involves the re-engineering of
critical processes and systems with an aim to achieve partnering
on all fronts, will roll out progressively from June 2000.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Authority said a multi-disciplinary
departmental task force has been set up to oversee and steer the
implementation plan mapped out after a two-month public
consultation exercise which ended last month.
</P>
<P>
"The overall response to the consultation has been very
encouraging. Most of the stakeholders and respondents agree that
there is an urgent need to uplift building quality and partnering
is the key to success in this reform," the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
