<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial on Iranian Jews Accused of Espionage Adjourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The first session of the closed-
door trial on 13 Iranian Jews accused of spying for Iran's arch
foes of the United States and Israel was adjourned Thursday and
postponed to May 1.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Ali Amiri, head of the justice department of the
southern Fars province, said the trial was put off upon the request
of a defense lawyer, though the accused had announced readiness for
defense.
</P>
<P>
He said the court made the decision with respect to the ideology
of the Jews and views of the accused that the timing of the trial
coincided with the Jewish feast of Passover, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The trial started Thursday morning in a conservative
revolutionary court in Shiraz, the capital city of Fars province,
the center of Iran's 35,000-strong Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
The families of eight Jews have chosen their defense lawyers and
the court have appointed lawyers for two others, while the three
who were released on bail have not appointed any lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyers called for a postponement of the trial as they
have limited time to go through details of the case, which has
aroused grave concern from the U.S., Israel and other European
countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Israel have denied any link between their
intelligence services and the Iranian Jews and have repeatedly
urged Iran to release the Jews since their arrest in March and
April last year. But Tehran has rejected the appeal as "
interference" in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian conservative judiciary has promised a "fair and
open" trial for the Jews and some judicial officials said that not
all of the 13 Jews will be charged with espionage.
</P>
<P>
Under the Iranian laws, the defendants might be sentenced to
death if they are convicted of spying for foreign countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
