<HEADLINE> Pakistan Urges U.S. to Talk with Taliban on Osama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Interior Minister
Moinuddin Haider said here on Thursday that he has asked the
United States to hold direct talks with the Afghan Taliban Militia
on the issue of Osama-bin-Laden.
</P>
<P>
On return from his 12-day visit to the United States and
Britain,the minister told a press conference that Osama-bin-Laden
is not in Pakistan but is living in Afghanistan, which is an
independent and sovereign country. He said he would raise the
issue of terrorism with Taliban's Interior minister who is
scheduled to visit Pakistan later this month.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has demanded Pakistan to impose severe trade sanctions
on Afghanistan to force the Taliban Militia to expel Osama-bin-
Laden. The demand was conveyed to Pakistan during a meeting
between Pakistan's Chief Executive General Pervez Musharraf and
FBI director, Louis J. Freeh in Lahore on April 6, a local
newspaper quoted their"western diplomatic sources" as saying.
</P>
<P>
The United States has charged Osama-bin-Laden with being
responsible for the explosion of U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania in August 1998. 
