<HEADLINE> Angola Suspends All Diamond Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government has
suspended all contracts on the purchase and sale of diamonds, the
Angolan Deputy Minister of Geology and Mining Carlos Sumbula said
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Luanda-based "Ecclesia" Radio, Sumbula
said that of the over-400 million-dollar annual revenue from the
sale of diamonds, only five million U.S. dollars go to the state
budget.
</P>
<P>
The decision to cancel the contracts is part of a strategy to
correct the irregularities existing in trading the precious stones
and to control the illegal diamond trafficking, said the deputy
minister.
</P>
<P>
The move had been confirmed earlier by the president of the
board of managers of the Angolan National Diamonds Company
(Endiama), Agostinho Gaspar, when addressing a program on the
state-owned TPA television.
</P>
<P>
Gaspar added that of the four ongoing projects for diamonds
mining in the country, the most profit one is the "Catoca"
project, which is located in the diamond-rich Lunda-norte province
and supported by companies from many countries including Russia,
Britain and Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
