<HEADLINE> Foreign Missions in Tanzania Urged to Verify Opposition's Accusation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government has
asked foreign missions to Tanzania to treat with caution claims on
human rights abuses by the opposition camp in the run-up to the
general elections in October.
</P>
<P>
When debating the proposed constitutional amendments in the
House of Representatives on the Indian Ocean island on Wednesday,
Zanzibar Deputy Chief Minister Omar Ramadhani Mapuri said the
foreign missions should in the first place verify the claims with
relevant authorities.
</P>
<P>
The minister said some foreign missions were the source of the
Isles political conflict which surfaced after the 1995 general
elections by siding with the opposition party of Civic United
Front (CUF).
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued last Thursday, the European Union
representatives in Dar es Salaam accused the Zanzibar government
of harassing CUF and being unwilling to implement an agreement
signed in June 1999 between the ruling Tanzanian Revolutionary
Party (CCM) and CUF aimed at resolving the political deadlock
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Mapuri cautioned there was a growing tendency for the
opposition to act irresponsibly and rush to the embassies accusing
the government of harassing it.
</P>
<P>
Experience has shown that supporters of opposition parties
purposely contravened the country's laws under the pretext of
multi-party democracy, Mapuri said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister of State of Zanzibar President's Office
Mohamed Ramia told the House that the government has invited the
new Commonwealth Secretary General to Tanzania to be elected soon
to have a first-hand experience of the implementation of the peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
According to the Commonwealth brokered accord, the Zanzibar
Electoral Commission should be reformed before the general
elections in October.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar's ruling CCM party, under President Salmin Amour,
claimed a narrow victory over the CUF in the 1995 elections, but
CUF questioned the result.
</P>
<P>
Political situation has become tense on the semi-autonomous
island off mainland Tanzania after 18 CUF activists have been put
in detention since December 1997 on sedition and treason charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
