<HEADLINE> Israel Plans to Develop New Missiles and Pilotless Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Israel is planning to develop
three new types of long-range missiles and two types of anti-
ballistic missile unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) to boost its
defense capability.
</P>
<P>
The Israel Air Force (IAF) will allocate approximately 30
billion U.S. dollars' budget for the research and development plan
in the next decade, the Ha'aretz daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the IAF is to upgrade its Python air-to-air missile to
a new generation, Python 5, with improved range and enhanced
precision and anti-electronic jamming capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Another air-to-air long-range missile with approximately 90
kilometers' range is also being planned.
</P>
<P>
A third type of missile will be an air-to-ground guided missile
aiming to destroy enemy's missile launchers.
</P>
<P>
To form a complete striking set, a type of UAV is currently
under IAF development, which is designed to carry these missiles.
The design objective of these UAVs is reportedly to float in the
air for as long as 60 hours and carry 10 missiles.
</P>
<P>
The striking set is in accordance with IAF's new tactical
strategy, which aims to attack missile launchers rather than
intercept missiles in the air.
</P>
<P>
Another UAV, which would be a stealth type, is being designed
for high altitude, distant operations and will be guided to hit
moving targets.
</P>
<P>
Quoting United States journal Aviation Week, the report also
revealed that the IAF is negotiating with the U.S. Defense
Department for the purchase of 50 F-22s, which is scheduled to
enter service in 6-7 years' time.
</P>
<P>
It is a related development regarding the missile and UAVs
research, according to the report, as the F-22, which is currently
undergoing tests, is widely regarded as the most advanced fighter
in the future and will be integrated into IAF's long-term strategy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
