<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for More Foreign Portfolio Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia critically needs foreign
portfolio investment (FPI) if it is to achieve a sustainable
economic growth following the privatization of its copper mines,
according to Lusaka Stock Exchange General Manager Charles Mate.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail on Thursday quoted Mate as saying that the
completion of the sale of the assets of Zambia Consolidated Copper
Mines (ZCCM) is not the end of the road for the country's search
for money to stimulate its development.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign portfolio investment is the critical answer as it will
 contribute to filling the financial gap to complement the
domestic savings of the country. It will provide the necessary
foreign exchange to support growth and development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mate said that the absence of the FPI will make the country's
growth very difficult as there are other hurdles that could come
especially in the area of Balance of Payments support.
</P>
<P>
He bemoaned the trend of a lot of money getting out of the
country over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
More foreign direct investment, institutional investment and
the guidelines on joint venture arrangements are some of the
pre-requisites to attracting FPI, said Mate.
</P>
<P>
Zambia recorded an increased net capital outflows and static
foreign direct investment (FDI) between 1996 and 1999 while FPI
maintained a negative trend, according to Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
FPI was negative 165 million U.S. dollars in 1999 and FDI
inflows were 200 million U.S. dollars, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Mate as saying mining, tourism, transport, energy and
 agriculture will play major roles in attracting FPI in the
post-ZCCM privatization period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
