<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania's Motor Sales, Production Plunge in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Both the sales and production
of Romania's motor vehicles suffered a dramatic fall in the first
quarter this year to 50 percent and 30 percent respectively from
year-ago levels, the Nine O'clock daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time since 1992 that the sales of motor
vehicles have dropped so significantly," Paul Schiancu, President
of the Association of Automotive Manufacturers and Importers (APIA)
, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sales of vehicles during the period nose-dived to less than
half of the level a year earlier, from 33,000 to only 13,600 units,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Dacia and Daewoo, Romania's two major car producers,
registered drastic falls in sales, with the former posting a 62
percent fall and the latter 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The first quarter of this year has been very bad," Schiancu
said, adding that "there are no signals that the situation will
significantly improve."
</P>
<P>
Motor vehicle production plummeted over 30 percent in the first
three months of this year, compared with the same period of 1999,
totaling less than 21,000 vehicles, he said.
</P>
<P>
The production of Dacia cars plunged 36 percent mainly because
of the falling sales, which have caused a heavy stock and forced
the management to stop the manufacturing operations for variable
periods of time. The production of Daewoo cars and Roman trucks
dropped 7 percent and 28 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Schiancu attributed the dismal situation in the auto market to
the general decline of purchasing power of the population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
