<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO: World Merchandise Trade to Grow Over 6.5 Percent in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The world merchandise trade growth
should reach 6.5 percent in the year 2000, the World Trade
Organization (WTO) predicted in its preliminary report published
here Thursday on trade developments in 1999 and the outlook for
this year.
</P>
<P>
Higher trade growth is possible, in particular, if the demand
in Western Europe and Japan pick up more strongly than currently
projected, according to the WTO report.
</P>
<P>
More robust growth of the world economy in 2000, together with
the carry-over effect due to the trade acceleration in the second
half of 1999, is projected to lead to export volume growth of at
least 6.5 percent, the WTO predicted in the report.
</P>
<P>
It said that most of this higher growth is expected to come
from Western Europe and to a lesser extent from Latin America, the
Middle East and the transition economies.
</P>
<P>
North America and the developing countries in Asia, which
recorded double digit import growth in 1999, are likely to expand
their imports less rapidly in 2000, and the projected deceleration
of North America's final demand should lead to less dynamic import
growth in 2000, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It cautioned that a sharp correction of the stock markets,
together with a marked slowing down of United States demand and
imports, could alter the trade forecast significantly. For example,
the United States merchandise trade deficit in 1999, at nearly 350
billion dollars, exceeded the total imports of Japan. And a
disruptive adjustment of the current external imbalances would
imply a major risk to trade growth in the near future, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The WTO said that the projections above were made on assumption
that the oil price will recede from its 30 U.S. dollars per barrel
level in the first quarter back to a range of 20 to 25 dollars and
that major financial market turbulence -- in particular a sudden
sharp correction of stock markets and the dollar rate -- can be
avoided in the remaining months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Global economic output is expected to accelerate from 3 percent
in 1999 to about 3.5 percent in 2000, the WTO said. In 2000, GDP
growth of industrial countries could expand by 3 percent or one
half percent faster than in 1999 as moderately lower growth in the
United States is more than offset by higher growth in Western
Europe and Japan. Latin America and the Middle East should see a
strong pick-up in their GDP growth after experiencing a stagnation
of output in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Higher growth is also projected for the transition and African
economies. GDP growth of the Asian developing countries is
projected to remain unchanged as the impact of the expansionary
fiscal policies and the rebuilding of inventories will be less
important in 2000 than in 1999, but offset by a strengthening of
fixed investment and private consumption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
