<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac on
Thursday inaugurated a new exhibition hall for master pieces of
primitive arts from Asia, Africa, Oceania, Arctic and America at
the Museum Louvre.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and former Prime Minister Alain
Juppe attended the inauguration at the 1,400-square-meter Pavillon
des Sessions, which is designed by French architect Jean-Michel
Wilmotte and gathers 117 pieces of sculptures.
</P>
<P>
The project was personally initiated by Chirac in 1995 and will
be expanded into a new museum of primitive arts, which is expected
to be built by 2004 near the Tower Eiffel by the Seine River.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Kerchache, Chirac's advisor for the future museum, said
that the exhibition is opened in the Louvre in order to show that
there is no difference in the value of arts across the world.
</P>
<P>
"In this museum where millions of people visit, it is to
demonstrate that there were great artists in all cultures, not
only in the West," he told the daily Le Figaro. 
</P>
