<HEADLINE> TV Projects Victory of South Korean Ruling Party in Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's ruling Millennium
Democratic Party (MDP) will become the biggest group in the
unicameral National Assembly, or parliament, by winning Thursday's
general elections, as showed by exit polls conducted by South
Korean TV stations.
</P>
<P>
The MBS TV predicted that the MDP will gain at least 127 seats
of the 273-member parliament while the main opposition Grand
National Party (GNP) will get 120 seats and the minor opposition
United Liberal Democrats (ULD) 17.
</P>
<P>
The MBS also showed that the Dear Democratic People's Party (
DDPP) will obtain three seats while other parties and independents
six seats.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a joint survey by South Korean KBS-TV and SBS-TV
forecast that the MDP will secure seats between 119 and 138 seats
and the GNP between 104 and 126.
</P>
<P>
Both televisions projected 12 seats for the ULD, one for the
DDPP, three for other parties and four for independents. The
margin of error for the KBS-SBS poll is plus or minus 3.1 to 4.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The three TV stations show that the MDP won all seats from its
political stronghold of North Cholla and South Cholla provinces
while the GDP got all from its political base North Kyongsang and
South Kyongsang provinces.
</P>
<P>
The general elections, the 16th in the country, began early
Thursday at 13,789 polling centers across the nation and ended in
the afternoon. A total of 1,176 runners are competing in the
elections.
</P>
<P>
Television reports said that the turnout was the lowest in the
country's history with less than 60 percent of more than 34
million eligible voters casting votes.
</P>
<P>
The final result of the elections will come out late Thursday
or Friday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
