<HEADLINE> Oman May Withdraw from World Cup Qualifiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Oman Football Association (OFA)
may withdraw from World Cup soccer qualifiers if the Asian
Football Confederation (AFC) turns down its request to host the
matches in their group, an OFA official said in Mascat, Oman on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The official said OFA had already agreed with Laos and the
Philippines for the Asian group one qualifiers to be played in
Oman in May 2001 but Syria had insisted on the matches being
played on a home and away basis.
</P>
<P>
"We talked to Laos and Philippines and they agreed to play all
the qualifying matches in Oman and the AFC approved it. However,
we now hear that the Asian soccer governing body might allow Syria
to have its way," the official said.
</P>
<P>
"It won't be fair if AFC turns down our request since the
majority of the teams in the group have already agreed to play in
Oman. If it does then we may have no choice but to reconsider our
participation to play the matches." 
</P>
