<HEADLINE> Divers to Wear Sonar Devices to Scare Away Sharks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Divers riding underwater
scooters will use sonar devices to scare away sharks at Sunday's
World Cup triathlon in Sydney Harbour.
</P>
<P>
However, event manager David Hansen said Thursday the divers
were there mainly to reassure international competitors who had
been worried by reports of shark attacks in Australia in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
Hansen said: "We don't see sharks as a problem. This is simply
a security blanket for the overseas competitors."
</P>
<P>
But he said the best deterrent for sharks was a large pack of
swimmers and the noise from motorised boats in place to shadow
athletes during the 1,500m swim from the steps of the Opera House.
</P>
<P>
A report commissioned by the Sydney Organising Committee for
the Olympic Games shows there has not been a shark attack in
Sydney Harbour in 208 years from May to November, and only one in
April. 
</P>
