<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Canada has offered to take in some 15,000 Palestinian
refugees when a permanent status agreement between Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority is reached, a senior Israeli
government official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official said that Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretian
made this offer to Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak during his
visit here this week.
</P>
<P>
Chretian is the first leader to make such a concrete offer, but
Barak has said in the past that he hopes the international
community will all help with this complicated issue and that many
countries will offer haven to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- An agreement was reached Wednesday between the Finance
Ministry, the labor unions and the Union of Civil Servants to end
the strike of more than 10,000 civil servants.
</P>
<P>
Work will resume Thursday in government offices, although some
of the unions favor opening the odds to the public only on
Sunday, "to allow for preparations."
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Security officials Wednesday ordered the release of 13 of the
15 Lebanese hostages being held in administrative detention in
Israel as bargaining chips for the freedom of captive Israeli
soldiers, following a Supreme Court decision upholding an appeal by
human rights attorney Zvi Rish.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who also holds the defense portfolio, said he respects
the court's decision, although he believes that Israel should
continue to hold the detainees for a certain period.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministry began preparing Wednesday for anticipated
petitions to the Supreme Court for the release of the remained two
prisoners Mustafa Dirani and Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid.
</P>
<P>
The state and military prosecutors believe that, unlike the
other detainees, it will be possible to convince the court that the
continued detention of Dirani and Obeid is necessary.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Members of One Israel and Meretz party were expressing a "
guarded optimism" Wednesday night on the chances of resolving the
coalition crisis in the wake of Wednesday's meeting between
Education Minister Yossi Sarid and his deputy minister Meshulam
Nahari .
</P>
<P>
It was the first one-on-one meeting between the two, of the
left-wing Meretz party and the ultraorthodox religious Shas party
respectively, since the escalation in recent months of the argument
over control of Shas's educational system.
</P>
<P>
Shas is demanding that Nahari be allowed to control the schools,
while Sarid insists he will not give Shas direct responsibility for
its own schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
