<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Moderate Culture Minister Resigns: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran's moderate Minister of Culture
and Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani has resigned his post amid
speculation that President Mohammed Khatami is considering a
reshuffle of his cabinet, a local newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Khatami had accepted Mohajerani's resignation and appointed
presidential advisor for higher education affairs Hadi Khaniki to
charge of the ministry, the conservative Tehran Times daily quoted
an informed source as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Mohajerani said on Monday at a press conference that he
had no intention to resign.
</P>
<P>
"My resignation would please certain dailies but I must say
there is no reason for them to be happy because I have not
resigned," he said.
</P>
<P>
The source declined to comment on Mohajerani's denial and gave
no specific reason for Mohajerani's resignation.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani held the post of deputy premier from 1985 to 1989.
After the post of premier was cancelled in 1989, he became vice
president in charge of parliamentary and legal affairs under former
President Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani, a founding member of the centralist Party of
Constructive Executives of Iran, has been under strong attack from
the conservatives who suffered serious setbacks in elections during
the past two years but still dominate most sensitive state organs.
</P>
<P>
He survived last May an impeachment motion by the conservative
Majlis (parliament) for his support of press freedom and vowed to
continue his policy to support the country's freedom-seeking press.
</P>
<P>
The minister said on Monday that his ministry would seek
legislation to annul the rights of any state organs to revoke the
licenses of any newspapers after the new Majlis with reformist
majority starts work in May.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been clouded by political tension since the sensitive
sixth parliamentary election in February, in which reformists
allied to President Khatami dealt a severe blow to the
conservatives by gaining more than 75 percent of the total 290
seats.
</P>
<P>
Pressure on the press has been building for the past few weeks
after the Iranian new year started on March 20, and several chiefs
and journalists of reformist newspapers have been summoned to
different courts while a chief-editor was put into prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
