<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Adopts Measures to Push Interest Rate Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Central Bank (CBN) has
reduced the minimum rediscount rate (MRR) from 18 percent to 17
percent in a bid to encourage borrowing.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, quoted a CBN
statement as saying Thursday that the essence of the downward
review was to influence indirectly the level and direction of
change in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
O.O. Akanji, director of Research of the Bank, said in Abuja
that the move was made in the light of the current fasting of
economic and market conditions, particularly the sustained decline
in the inflation rate and the inflow of funds into the banking
system.
</P>
<P>
Banking interest rate in the country, which stands as high as
about 30 percent in most cases, severely hindered the growth of
the manufacturing sector, said experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
