<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows More Than Half of Romanian Students Want to Work Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 13 (Xinhua) -- More than half of Romanian
students would prefer to work abroad after graduation, according
to a latest poll of Romanian university students.
</P>
<P>
The poll, published Thursday on Nine O'clock daily, surveyed 1,
598 students from 66 departments in 12 universities. The results
show that 67.5 percent of the students questioned in state
universities and 61.4 percent in private universities want to
emigrate.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the students interviewed would prefer to work
for foreign private companies, whereas only 12.4 percent would
prefer a Romanian private company and 11.3 percent said they would
like to work for a state company.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of the poll carried out by the National Public
Opinion Institute, the Students Organization in the Bucharest
University organized a debate which was attended by Romanian
politicians. Participants in the debate said "brain drain" cannot
be stopped at present in Romania.
</P>
<P>
Romania's former president Ion Iliescu attributed the trend to
bureaucracy, the lack of stimulating work environments, and the
inaccessibility of education opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is that young people do not have any prospective
to affirm themselves in the country," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
