<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merchandise Exports of Developing Countries Increase in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries' merchandise
exports in 1999 increased by 8.5 percent, about two times faster
than the global average, the World Trade Organization (WTO)
announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In its preliminary report on trade developments in 1999, the
WTO noted that throughout the 1990s, developing countries' exports
rose faster than world trade, with the exception of 1998.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the share of developing countries was 27.5 percent for
merchandise exports and 23 percent for commercial services exports,
both more than 4 percentage points higher than those in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The global commercial services trade accelerated only slightly
in 1999, as the recovery in Asia and higher growth in North
America were partly offset by lower growth in western Europe as
well as a major contraction in Latin America and the transition
economies, the WTO said.
</P>
<P>
The global output and trade strengthened considerably in the
second half of 1999, thereby improving the prospects for higher
growth in the current year. The recovery in Asia and continued
high demand growth in North America contributed most to global
trade expansion last year.
</P>
<P>
World commodity output in 1999 increased by 1.5 percent, the
same as in 1998. A fall in mining sector output (in particular oil)
contrasted with stronger growth in the manufacturing sector (e.g.
electronic goods and automobiles). The global output of services
industries exceeded commodity output growth. The world GDP growth
increased from 2 percent in 1998 to 3 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
World merchandise trade value increased by 3.5 percent in 1999,
faster than commercial services trade. Nevertheless, for the 1990-
99 period as a whole, the commercial services trade still expanded
slightly faster than merchandise trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
