<HEADLINE> Construction of Int'l Shipping Center in Shanghai (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Confronted with fierce
competition from surrounding international ports, Shanghai, the
largest port in China's mainland, has stepped up efforts to
achieve its goal of becoming an international shipping center.
</P>
<P>
Ruan Yanhua, deputy director of the Administrative Committee of
the Pudong New Area, said that the city is now launching the third
stage of the newly developed Waigaoqiao Port Area in Pudong, while
preliminary preparations for the fourth stage are underway.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several years, billions of dollars have already
been spent on deep water berths in the city, said Gu Gang, deputy
director of the Int'l Shipping Center Construction Administration
under the Shanghai Municipal People's Government.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Gu said that a
feasibility study is being conducted on a new large-scale
container wharf between the Dayangshan Island and the Xiaoyangshan
Island in the East China Sea, 27.5 km from the city.
</P>
<P>
Investors from the United States, Britain, Denmark and a dozen
other countries have contacted Shanghai, expressing interest in
planning, designing and constructing the wharf.
</P>
<P>
Now operating container shipping routes to more than 120 ports
across the world, Shanghai aims to increase container handling to
8.5 million TEUs (twenty-feet equivalent units) by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say this will not only accelerate the city's endeavor
to become an international trade center but also be conducive to
the development of the Yangtze River area and developing the
western part of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
