<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Suffers Severe Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Four consecutive years of
severe drought have evaporated the drinking water of nearly 1.5
million people in north China's Hebei Province which surrounds
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Hebei is facing a shortage of 800 million cubic meters of water,
said Wang Jun, deputy director of the provincial flood control and
drought relief office.
</P>
<P>
About 2.8 million hectares of cultivated land is now endangered
by the long drought, and 380,000 head of livestock are also in
dire need of water.
</P>
<P>
The province has transferred more than 200 million cubic meters
of water from China's second largest river, the Yellow River. Some
counties, such as Zhangjiakou in the northern part of the province,
have bought water from the neighboring province of Shanxi in order
to save the local crops.
</P>
<P>
This year's Spring has been dry and hot, with more sand storms
than in normal years, a combination making the drought much worse,
Wang Jun said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
