<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laid-off Workers Become Qualified Nurses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-three laid-off workers
have become nurses qualified to look after women during their
month of confinement after giving birth.
</P>
<P>
They are the first group of professional nursery maids in China.
After receiving professional hospital training, they are able to
help young parents take care of new born babies scientifically,
and help relieve the parents' burdens.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that nearly two-thirds of the 284 people polled
said they would like to have such aid at home when they have a
baby.
</P>
<P>
This month of confinement is of special importance to Chinese
women after they give birth, and traditionally grandmothers are
invited to take care of the mother and her baby during the first
four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
About 506,000 laid-off workers in Liaoning, China's traditional
heavy industrial base in the northeast, found new jobs last year,
and about half of them have become housekeepers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
