<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction of Int'l Shipping Center in Shanghai (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Analysts say that Shanghai has had to compete with many other
Asian ports such as Kobe, Tokyo and Yokohama and Pusan in the
Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai needs to take immediate measures to resolve two major
problems, namely, a shortage in container berths and a relatively
shallow navigation channel at the mouth of the Yangtze, where the
port is located.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics indicate that Shanghai's container
handling capacity has fallen behind the needs of clients although
it has been surging at an annual rate of 25 percent over the past
decade, with capacity reaching 4.21 million TEUs, ranking seventh
in the world. Hong Kong ranks first with over 16 million TEUs.
</P>
<P>
Gu said that the prospect of China's entry into the World Trade
Organization has called for even faster expansion and upgrading of
the port. "If we don't speed up the construction of the
international shipping center, multinational shipping companies
will turn to other ports," Gu said.
</P>
<P>
To date, overseas shipping companies, including the world's top
20 container shipping companies, have established over 80
subsidiaries in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
China's three biggest shipping companies, the Container
Transport Company of the China Ocean Shipping Corporation, the
China Shipping Group, and Sinotrans Container Shipping Company
have all moved their headquarters to Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
