<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment Increasingly Shifts to Private Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Employment opportunities in urban
areas of China are shifting from public sectors to private sectors
at an accelerating pace, official figures show.
</P>
<P>
According to a national survey conducted by the National Bureau
of Statistics (NBS), The number of self-employed individuals in
urban areas in 1998 was 53 times greater than 20 years ago.
Meanwhile, the proportion of public sector employees was nearly
half of that in two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the self-employed accounted for 11 percent of all
urban employment, compared with 0.2 percent in 1978.
</P>
<P>
From 1978 to 1998, employees in government-run sectors
decreased from 78.3 percent to 43.8 percent. The growth rate of
self-employed persons has far exceeded that of the urban
employment.
</P>
<P>
Over the 20 years, urban employment increased by 1.2 times to
206.8 million. More than 22 million of them are self-employed, and
over 90 million of them are in public sectors.
</P>
<P>
Employees in urban collective enterprises slumped from 21.5
percent to 9.5 percent in the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
