<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palace Museum Adds 240,000 Relics to its Collection in Half Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Palace Museum has added more
than 240,000 treasured relics to its collection since the founding
of the People's Republic of China in 1949, according to a recently
published data book.
</P>
<P>
The book is published by the Beijing Forbidden City Publishing
House and provides readers with specific information on as many as
240,888 items, most of which were donated by governmental organs.
</P>
<P>
According to the book, the State Administration of Cultural
Heritage (SACH) gave 101,772 relics to the museum and another 21,
875 were donated by individuals.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the reserves were bought by the museum from antique
shops, auction houses, and private collectors.
</P>
<P>
The relics include some priceless items such as masterpieces
created by well-known calligraphers and painters including Wang
Xianzhi, Li Bai, Han Huang, Gu Hongzhong, Lu Ji, Zhan Ziqian,
Zhang Xian, Shen Zhou, and Shi Tao.
</P>
<P>
As the imperial residence of the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (
1644-1911) dynasties, the Forbidden City, another name for the
Palace Museum, remains China's largest group of ancient structures.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO) added the Palace Museum to its World
Heritage List in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Established on October 10, 1925, the museum's collection
includes nearly one million items.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man-Raised Sturgeons Born in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- About 13,000 sturgeons were born
to an eight-year-old man-raised sturgeon in Beijing recently. This
was the first time Chinese experts succeeded in producing such
sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
The experiment was made by the National Fresh Water Fishery
Research Center, and the Beijing Science and Technology Committee,
according to today's Beijing Daily.
</P>
<P>
The sturgeon, which is considered a "living fossil," has been
in existence for more than 200 million years. Elements drawn from
its cartilage can help prevent cancer, and its meat and internal
organs can also be made into medicines, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Sturgeon roe is famous as "black caviar," and its skin can be
made into expensive leather.
</P>
<P>
Companies in Beijing began to raise this fish of high economic
value using artificial methods in 1996, but they had to buy the
roe or fries from European countries.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the success of the artificial reproduction of
sturgeon may help local companies find a cheaper way to raise the
rare fish.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
