<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dangerous Cult Exposed in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A dangerous religious cult has
brainwashed at least 70 youths in Cypriot capital of Nicosia and
more in southern coast town of Limassol, the Cyprus Mail newspaper
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Andreas Phylachtou, speaking Wednesday at a news conference
organized by the Pancyprian Union of parents, confirmed he "had
lost" his daughter to the Disciples of Christ.
</P>
<P>
Phylachtou said with tears in his eyes that he had found out
almost two years ago that his 27-year-old daughter was part of what
he claimed was a devious, money-orientated cult that hid its
identity behind offshore companies operating on the island.
</P>
<P>
Phylachtou, on behalf of parents whose children had fallen
victims to the cult, said "our children were normal until they lost
control of themselves and their personalities."
</P>
<P>
He said their children suddenly decided to give up their studies
and dealt with nothing else than the cult's organization and its
frequent meetings. If they miss one meeting they will receive
dozens of phone calls from the organization chief.
</P>
<P>
"They hold the Bible acting as if they were hypnotized and try
to draw more people into the cult in gyms, colleges and other
learning institutes," Phylachtou said, noting that the children
have paid money now and then to the cult.
</P>
<P>
Phylachtou said he had managed to infiltrate a cult meeting two
weeks ago, and had found out that a policeman was involved in the
cult's organization.
</P>
<P>
He exposed that some foreign young people from the U.S. and
other countries are spreading the religion. The cult paid their
tuition fee at the University of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
According to the Pancyprian Union of Parents, the Disciples of
Christ are known internationally as a highly dangerous cult, and
based their beliefs on readings of the New Testament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
