<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt to Lower Medicine Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
given itself six months to bring down prices of medicines in the
country as part of the Estrada administration's efforts to make
life-saving health care available to all Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Romualdez, secretary of the Department of Health (DOH),
said Thursday his office and the Department of Trade and Industry(
DTI) are studying several measures to achieve this goal.
</P>
<P>
"We are now considering some approaches so we can bring down
the prices of medicines in the next six months," Romualdez said in
a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada earlier noted that prices of medicine
in his country cost 10 times more than in other Asian countries,
such as India.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez said his office has been meeting with representatives
of the pharmaceutical industry to find ways of bringing down
medicine prices.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, DTI Secretary Mar Roxas disclosed that the government
is
finalizing negotiations with foreign drug manufacturers to bring
in low-priced quality medicines into the country.
</P>
<P>
Roxas said medicine manufacturers from India were the first to
discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
The DTI chief noted that aside from accelerating the process of
bringing in low-priced medicines into the country, the government
is also making sure that quality control is strictly observed in
the importation of these goods.
</P>
<P>
To ensure these imported medicines do not get into the hands of
private distributors who may sell them at the usual steep prices,
the government will pass them on to the DOH, which will, in turn,
hand them out to government hospitals, Roxas said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
