<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Step Up Cooperation on Immigration Matters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines on Thursday urged
its fellow members in the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (
ASEAN)to strengthen cooperation on immigration and consular
matters and in fighting transnational crime, reports reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening of the ASEAN high level experts group
meeting on immigration and consular matters in Lapu-Lapu City in
the central Philippines, Immigration Commissioner Rufus Rodriguez
said the meeting will also forge closer economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez said the two-day meeting will discuss the proposed
development of an ASEAN plan of action on immigration and consular
matters, a directory of immigration focal points and a regional
approach for confronting the problem of human trafficking.
</P>
<P>
He said that the meeting will concretize strategies and action
plans to enhance further cooperation on immigration and consular
matters which will be presented for final approval at the 4th
meeting of ASEAN director-generals of immigration departments and
heads of consular divisions to be held in the Philippines in
October.
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to a very substantive exchange of ideas and
proposals on how we could further elevate and strengthen our
cooperation among ASEAN immigration and consular officials to
attain regional peace, security and prosperity," Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
Thirty two delegates, composed of immigration officials and
representatives from consular divisions of ministries of foreign
affairs from the 10 ASEAN countries, are attending the conference.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Philippine delegation is expected to
present the result of the Asian Regional Initiative Against
Trafficking of Women and Children conference held in Manila on
March 29-31.
</P>
<P>
Proposals for a regional approach in combating human
trafficking and adoption of a common ASEAN entry visa for tourists
will also be discussed in the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
