<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Conservationists Opposed to Reopening Turtle Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Fund for Animal
Welfare (IFAW) is completely opposed to relaxing the ban on trade
in hawksbill turtle, according to a statement released here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cuba and Dominica have submitted two proposals to the ongoing
11th meeting of the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES) held in Nairobi on April 10-20.
</P>
<P>
They demanded transfer of hawksbill turtle from Appendix I,
which bans any trade, to Appendix II, which permits regulated
trade. They also seek approval to make one shipment of 6,900
kilograms of shell stockpile to Japan.
</P>
<P>
The conservation organization feared that the resumption of
international trade will stimulate the stockpiling of shell by
other countries and the illegal killing of hawksbill turtles
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
More than 135 respected sea turtle experts and conservationists
from over 40 countries have also publicly opposed to the Cuban
proposals, signing on to a petition drafted by the IFAW.
</P>
<P>
"Reopening the trade in this already critically endangered
turtle will encourage further illegal trade of shell," said IFAW's
species campaigner Sarah Tyack. "Turtle conservation projects
throughout the Caribbean as well as the hawksbill will suffer if
the proposals are passed."
</P>
<P>
The issue on hawksbill turtle trade has maintained on CITES
Appendix I since 1977. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Members Urged to Increase Fish Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) have been urged to increase
fish production so as to reach the international consumption
standard.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a SADC workshop on a proposed fisheries protocol
here on Wednesday, Zambian Fisheries Permanent Secretary Russell
Mulele said the region has potential to increase fish production,
Zambia Daily Mail reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mulele said the main challenge faced by SADC states is that of
low fish consumption which stands at nine kilograms per person per
year as opposed to the World Health Organization's recommended
consumption of 17 kilograms per person per year.
</P>
<P>
Mulele said that the importance of increasing production and
productivity of the fisheries sector as well as sustainable use of
the fish resources should not be underrated as this can contribute
positively to the overall economic growth and development of the
SADC region.
</P>
<P>
He said since most of the fisheries resources are shared among
member states in terms of lakes and river systems, a legal
protocol should be introduced for the benefit of rapid growth of
the fisheries sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
