<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adjusts Glucide Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A nearly 50-year-old glucide
production line has been dismantled here recently, marking the
beginning of China's effort in a nation-wide adjustment in glucide
production.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua has learned that over the past decade, repeating
construction of glucide production enterprises doubled the output
of glucide, reaching 30,000 tons annually.
</P>
<P>
Excessive sales of glucide caused 125 sugar plants stop
production, with 125,000 workers losing their jobs, and badly
harmed the interest of 15 million sugar farmers.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has set a good example for the nation-wide adjustment
by dismantling the production line, the first of its like in China,
said Shi Wanpeng, vice-minister in charge of the State Economic
and Trade Commission (SETC).
</P>
<P>
To protect an orderly competition among sugar production
enterprises and promote the normal development of rural economy,
the SETC has decided to close nine of the country's 14 glucide
production enterprises.
</P>
<P>
After the adjustment, China's annul glucide output will be
reduced to about 1,400 tons, about 28,600 tons less than now, and
the annul glucide output capacity will be kept at 18,400 tons,
according to the SETC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Aids Border Area Pupils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Government of southwest China's
Yunnan Province has made an financial-aid plan to provide 18
million yuan (2.16 million US dollars) per year as tuition for 120,
000 poverty-stricken pupils.
</P>
<P>
These primary school students are living in 123 villages and
townships of 25 counties bordering Vietnam, Laos and Burma.
</P>
<P>
In the new semester this year, each of the students received
150 yuan aid from the provincial government as education tuition
and fees on books and studying utensils.
</P>
<P>
A local educational official said that the plan aims at helping
the poverty-stricken students, especially ethnic pupils living in
border areas, complete the country's nine-year compulsory
education.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has set up a special education fund
in 1996, which offers 2.55 million yuan annually to poverty-
stricken students in border counties, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
The province's border line totals 4,060 km long. Thanks to the
effort of local educational departments, 99 percent of the school-
aged children in the border areas can now attend school, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
