<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Ask for The Same Pension as Men </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Women's federations in China
have been receiving letters from women intellectuals who want the
same retirement pay as their male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The All-China Women's Federation (ACWF) have already sent
letters to the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress (NPC) and the Ministry of Personnel requesting them to
reconsider existing regulation concerning the retirement age and
pension for men and women.
</P>
<P>
 Regulations stipulate that female intellectuals should retire
at 55 years old, while their male counterparts can retire at 60.
Retired women receive less pension because they retire earlier.
</P>
<P>
 Employees, who work for the government or state-run
enterprises for more than 35 years can enjoy a pension, which is
88 percent of their salary, according to state regulations. But
those who work for more than 30 years can only receive 82 percent
of their original salary after retirement.
</P>
<P>
 Some local governments have issued policies to change the
current situation. For example, Shanghai has issued regulation
which extend jobs for those with higher degrees.
</P>
<P>
The Wuhan municipal government has issued regulations
allowing female government employees to enjoy the same pension as
their male counterparts though they will still retire at 55.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Ministry of Personnel said that they are
waiting for decisions from the NPC Standing Committee to make
revisions to existing regulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Contamination Often Ignored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Contaminated fruit and vegetables
are often consumed by people without realizing that they have been
sprayed with poisonous pesticides.
</P>
<P>
A 1998 study of fruit and vegetables on the market in Beijing
revealed that 20 percent of the samples contained pesticide
residues that exceed the state standards, according to "China
Youth Daily".
</P>
<P>
Lu Xirong, a poisoning control expert with the Chinese Academy
of Preventive Medicine blames poor production management, citing
that some growers have no idea about the pesticides they use. Some
even intentionally spray banned pesticides on vegetables and fruit.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 cases of food poisoning caused by poisonous pesticides
were reported to the Ministry of Health last year. More tan 100
people died and 5,000 people fell seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
Lu urged governmental departments concerned to regulate the
pesticide market and give more instructions to both manufacturers
and users.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
