<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Bee Industry Threatened by Pest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's bee industry is
being threatened by a pest called "Varroa bee mite."
</P>
<P>
Television New Zealand reported Thursday that the New Zealand
Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry (MAF) is investigating the
case to determine the scale of infestations.
</P>
<P>
Recent discovery of the Varroa bee mite in hives on South
Auckland properties has resulted in MAF declaring Wednesday a
biosecurity alert for a large area in and around the Auckland
region on the country's North Island. MAF fears the bug may have
also spread to Otago on South Island.
</P>
<P>
The Varroa bee mite is spread by bees and in time kills the
entire hive. The bug is regarded as the most serious threat ever
faced by the multi-million-dollar industry in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand has an about a million U.S. dollar trade in
exporting live bees, and a more than 10 million U.S. dollar honey
industry.
</P>
<P>
Until now, New Zealand and Australia have been considered the
only major bee-keeping countries free of the Varroa mite.
</P>
<P>
MAF believes the mite may have been present undetected for up
to five-years. It was reported that major outbreaks in Britain and
the United States have wiped out over half of bee populations
there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
