<HEADLINE> Britain Offers Aide for Facilitator of National Dialogue in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain has offered a technical
advisor to the facilitator of the national dialogue in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) in an effort to help secure
peace in the country, Zambia Daily Mail reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Former President of Botswana Ketumile Masire is the facilitator
of the DRC national dialogue appointed by the Organization of
Africa Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the British High Commission (embassy)
in Lusaka said on Wednesday in a statement that the advisor,
Philip Winter, will begin his work in Gaborone, Botswana, this
week.
</P>
<P>
Winter has worked in Central Africa for 20 years and has a
background of financial and business management and political
analysis.
</P>
<P>
He would assist the facilitator in all aspects of the national
dialogue including coordinating support from the international
donors, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Britain also said it was ready to provide more support to help
implement the Lusaka cease-fire agreement signed last July and
August.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was the only logical way out of the impasse
between the Laurent Kabila administration and the rebels who waged
a conflict to topple kabila from power in August 1998, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
