<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge Gap in Annual Salaries for CEOs in China's State Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey by the National
Statistics Bureau (NSB) shows a blaring discrepancy in annual
salaries for CEOs in state-owned enterprises, which range from 2,
000 to more than one million yuan, China Business has reported.
</P>
<P>
The survey was carried out among company heads in Beijing,
Shanghai and Chongqing municipalities, and in provinces of Jiangsu,
Shandong, Henan, Hubei, Guangdong and Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
The gap in annual salaries for CEOs varied from region to
region and from company to company.
</P>
<P>
In southwest China's Sichuan Province, the highest annual
salary for a CEO stood at more than one million yuan, 200 times
the average income of employees in his enterprise. The lowest
annual salary for a CEO is 25,000 yuan, only 5.8 times that of
his employees.
</P>
<P>
The difference is smaller in Henan Province, where the top pay
was 54,000 yuan, five times the average income of employees, and
the lowest only 3,720 yuan, the same as employees.
</P>
<P>
The payment system, in which payroll is calculated in annual
term, has been in place in some state-owned enterprises in those
provinces and municipalities in recent years. The system was
designed to encourage creativeness and improving management skill
among CEOs while helping bring forth a talent contingent of
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
NSB analysts said the problem, or huge gap, emerging from the
new practice in recent years, indicate the newly introduced
payment system still needs regulating and supervising. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0252 </DOCNO>
