<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh to Face Criticism from Donors  (by Pan Xiaozhu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The government of Bangladesh is
likely to face a wave of criticism from donor countries at the
Bangladesh Development Forum meeting that begins in Paris Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is attended by representatives of bilateral donors
and multilateral agencies contributing to Bangladesh's socio-
economic development. Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria leads
the Bangladesh official delegation to the meeting arranged by the
World Bank (WB) which is the official coordinator for the donors.
</P>
<P>
Pervasive corruption, the thorny political scenario, slow pace
of institutional reforms, fragile economic situation and lack of
infrastructure facilities are some of the issues that might create
the ground for the likely grouse of donors, the daily Financial
Express reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Donors have already indicated that the aid flow to Bangladesh
in the coming fiscal year would hover between 1.8 billion U.S.
dollars and 2.2 billion dollars. The development partners,
meanwhile, hinted that the level of assistance would depend mostly
on the pace of reforms.
</P>
<P>
"This assistance could be significantly higher if the pace of
reform was accelerated," said a letter from the WB's Country
Director in Bangladesh, on behalf of the donor countries and
agencies, to the Bangladesh's finance minister by the end of the
last month.
</P>
<P>
It said that "the development partners emphasized that the
realization of even the lower figure will depend crucially on
accelerated progress in policy and institutional reform and faster
utilization of existing aid in the pipeline."
</P>
<P>
According to the letter, under almost any circumstances, the
fiscal performance of the country in the current fiscal (1999-2000)
year is likely to decline as compared to that in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal performance in 2000 so far shows signs of a further
deterioration, said the WB, urging the government of Bangladesh to
expedite its revenue collections through special efforts and take
austerity measures in case of expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The country's macro-economic situation was almost sound during
most of the 1990s. "However, there has recently been some slippage
in the macro-economic framework," the WB's letter said.
</P>
<P>
The external current account deficit was on average below three
percent of GDP during the fiscal 1990-1998 and the foreign
exchange reserve level was at over three months of imports. The
overall budget deficit averaged around 4.8 percent of GDP per
annum, with domestic financing limited to 1.1 percent of GDP per
annum.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth has also dropped to 4.8 percent in fiscal 1999
from the average growth rate of 5 percent during 1990-1998. The WB,
however, expected a 5.4 percent growth in current fiscal thanks to
another bumper crop.
</P>
<P>
To generate productive employment and reduce poverty, the WB
highlighted the urgency for accelerating the country's export-
oriented manufacturing and service sectors.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing growth, according the WB, continues to remain
weak due to loss of competitiveness, infrastructure bottlenecks
and lack of social stability.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector recently lost some of its dynamism
after growing impressively at 7.7 percent per annum during fiscal
1990-98.The growth dropped sharply to less than 3.2 percent in
fiscal 1999 and this sluggishness continued into the fiscal 2000.
</P>
<P>
The letter attributed this to "higher cost of doing business
and loss of competitiveness" both in the domestic and
international markets due to increased political instability and
slower reform.
</P>
<P>
The export growth, however, recovered to 7.2 percent through
December 1999. The recovery could continue during the rest of the
fiscal year if Bangladesh can take advantage of strong growth
momentum of exports volumes in North America, Europe and Asia, the
WB letter said.
</P>
<P>
Besides progress in institutional reforms, the most discussed
issue at the Paris meeting will be the rampant corruption in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Donors believe that if Bangladesh could reduce corruption level
to those prevailing in countries with the highest reputation for
honest dealing could add between 2.1 to 2.9 percent to the annual
per capita GDP growth, the WB letter said, adding that this could
lower the country's poverty by 25 percent. The judgment is that
per capita income in a corruption free Bangladesh could have
nearly doubled to 700 U.S.dollar instead of 350.
</P>
<P>
Donors will also discuss the country's political situation. The
Financial Express Thursday quoted a paper prepared by the Local
Consultative Group of donors as saying that political disruption
in the country "affects the prospects of democratic transition and
the climate for foreign investment."
</P>
<P>
The donors also expressed their willingness to hold the
discussions at the soonest for the assessment of their possible
assistance for the next parliamentary elections in the country
scheduled in 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian King in Good Condition After Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Belgian King Albert II was
operated early on Thursday for a heart bypass remedy and was in "
good" condition, his doctor said.
</P>
<P>
The operation took two and a half hours at the Hospital Onze
Lieve Vrouw d'Alost, where Doctor Hugo van Ermen announced the
result of the operation and the condition of the king.
</P>
<P>
"The king is doing well," said the doctor, chief of the
hospital's cardio-vascular department.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Prime Minister Guy Verhofstadt has decided to halt his
vacation at Toscane and return to Brussels Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The king and Queen Fabiola had scheduled to receive the
visiting Jordanian king Wednesday, but only the queen and Prince
Laurent received the Jordanian king and his family instead.
</P>
<P>
King Albert II and Queen Fabiola just paid a state visit to the
Netherlands, the second royal visit in more than 40 years. The
Belgian royals last visited the Netherlands in 1959 while an
unofficial visit was made in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
During the April 4-6 visit to the Netherlands, the Belgian king
and queen visited an urbanization project, a humanitarian project
for disadvantaged children, the headquarters of the Organization
for the Protection of Chemical Weapons and the Hague Municipal
Museum.
</P>
<P>
They also met with Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok. 
</P>
</TEXT>
