<HEADLINE> Xinhua Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, April 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian central bank, Bank Indonesia, predicted
economic growth between 4 and 5 percent in the second quarter of
this year compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Based on the projection, the gross domestic product (GDP) could
expand 3 or 4 percent for the year, according to Bank Indonesia
Governor Sjahril Sabirin. (Indonesia-Growth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) predicted
a financial recovery this year for most Latin American countries,
although there still exists a potential for vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
Recovery will be realized by the increase in domestic demand,
investments and exports, said an IMF report from Washington. (IMF-
L.America-Recovery)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PANAMA -- Panamanian thermo-electric company Enron will build
an underwater pipeline between Colombia and Panama to provide
natural gas to this Central American country's thermoelectric
companies.
</P>
<P>
Vice Minister of Panama's Domestic Trade, Ernesto Fernandez,
said Wednesday that the pipeline will help stabilize oil prices,
which often affect the power sector. (Panama-Colombia-Pipeline)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The World Wildlife Foundation announced Wednesday
in a news release that it completely objected to Cuba's proposal
to reopen the international trade in Hawksbill turtle.
</P>
<P>
"We shouldn't reopen the trade because controls in the main
importing country, Japan, are inadequate, the status of the turtle
populations in the Caribbean is unclear, and regional management
is patchy," said Elizabeth Kemf, WWF Species Information Manager,
in her newly published report. (WWF-Turtle-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The volume of retail trade was up in both the
European Union and the euro zone in January this year, Eurostat
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical bureau of the European
community said that the retail sales were up by 3.0 percent for
the 15-nation bloc and up by 2.3 percent in the 11-nation euro
zone, compared with the figures in January last year. (EU-Euro
Zone-Retail Sales)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States, in the "soft landing"
economists have long been seeking, will grow 4.4 percent this year
and then slow to 3 percent in 2001, the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) predicted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, in its twice-yearly World Economic Outlook, said the U.
S. economy would likely ease to a "soft landing." But it cautioned
there was no evidence that growth, boosted by rising stock prices,
would slow on its own. (IMF-US-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Four southern African countries are seeking
permission to sell more ivory from the ongoing 11th conference of
the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species in
Nairobi, saying highly controlled ivory trade will benefit their
countries.
</P>
<P>
Botswana delegation head Garyland Kombani told Xinhua on
Wednesday that the habitat for the species became too small since
106,000 elephants in his country occupied an area that could
handle only 50,000. (S.Africa-Ivory-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) predicted
Wednesday that the world economy will expand by a strong 4.2
percent this year, the best showing since 1988, with growth
continuing at a still-strong 3.9 percent in 2001. (IMF-World
Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France said on Wednesday that it will not impose
economic sanctions against Myanmar or order the withdrawal of the
oil group TotalFina from the country.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) decided on Monday to prolong and add
new measures to the sanctions against Myanmar, which were imposed
in 1996, because of what it called "violation of human rights" by
the military government there.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry said on Wednesday that the EU
sanctions do not comprise economic sanctions. (France-Myanmar-EU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The flow of foreign direct investment (FDI) into
India tripled during the 1990s despite its decrease in the Asia-
Pacific region during the decade, a report by the U.N. Conference
on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said Wednesday. (India-Foreign
Investment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The Kenyan government will sell 49 percent stake in
the Telkom Kenya Company which operates the country's
telecommunication infrastructure, Kenyan Finance Minister Chris
Okemo has said. (Kenya-Company) 
</P>
