<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Political Parties Locked in Close Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 34 million South Korean
voters are going to the polls Thursday to elect the 16th National
Assembly, or parliament, of the country, with no single party
likely to win a great majority.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's poll to elect 273 legislators, including 46
distributed to parties in proportion to voters, out of 1,176
runners, is believed a watershed for political stability for the
remaining tenure of President Kim Dae-jung, which will last to
early 2002.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Kim Dae-jung's government may become a lame duck
if his ruling Millennium Democratic Party (MDP) loses by a wide
margin to the biggest opposition Grand National Party (GNP).
</P>
<P>
The result of the poll is expected to critically affect
President Kim's political and economic reform and even the
scheduled inter-Korean summit on June 12-14.
</P>
<P>
At present, the MDP controls 98 seats of the parliament while
the GNP occupies 120 and the small opposition United Liberal
Democrats (ULD) 48.
</P>
<P>
Voters' attention is focused on which of the two parties will
become the largest group in the unicameral parliament for a four-
year term.
</P>
<P>
Both the ruling and opposition parties are expected to win some
100 seats and the ULD and and independents are likely to share the
remainder.
</P>
<P>
The ruling MDP has pleaded for voters to back its candidates,
saying its defeat would hamper the drive reform by President Kim
while the opposition Grand National Party has called for voters to
pass "stern" judgement on Kim's "mismangement of state affairs."
</P>
<P>
Observors said the outcome of the elections in politically
natural Seoul and Kyonggy province is crucial, given that most
voters cast ballots by regional lines.
</P>
<P>
On the strength of overwhelming support from their respective
political strongholds of the Cholla and Kyongsang provinces, the
the MDP and the GDP were locked in a fierce battle to dominate the
capital city and its vicinities, which account for 43 percent of
the total 227 constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the historic agreement signed in Beijing for an
inter-Korean summit in Pyongyang on June 12-14 this year will help
the ruling party's candidates.
</P>
<P>
The MDP promised a better life for the middle class and the
needy, saying that President Kim need popular support to continue
his reforms.
</P>
<P>
"Voters should give us the power so that President Kim can
produce accomplishments in the inter-Korean summit and keep
working for the people and the country," said MDP Chairman Lee In-
je.
</P>
<P>
However, the GNP has dealt a blow to the ruling party with the
astronomical amount of the national debt and other economic
matters.
</P>
<P>
"Voters should back the GNP as it is the only force that could
effective hold the ruling camp in check," said GNP secretary Suh
Chung-won.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ULD President Lee Han-dong said if the MDP and
GNP secured a majority, the next parliament would be thrown into
even deeper confusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
