<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's General Elections Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The election will choose between the ruling Millennium
Democratic Party and the largest opposition Grand National Party.
One or the other will dominate the parliament and decisively
influence President Kim Dae-jung's future policies regarding the
country's political and economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Recent surveys by the National Election Commission predicted a
turnout below 60 percent, one of the lowest for the country. More
than 34.4 million eligible voters, an increase of 1.99 million or
6.3 percent from the previous election in 1996, are expected to
take part in the voting, which will end at 6 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They will elect 273 legislators, including 46 under the
proportional representation system, out of 1,176 runners. Ballot
counting will be going on in 244 places throughout Friday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
