<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Attorney General Fails to Get Deal on Cuban Boy's Custody </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno failed late Wednesday to work out a deal after meeting
relatives of the six-year-old Cuban shipwreck survivor Elian
Gonzalez in Miami.
</P>
<P>
Reno had a three-hour meeting with the relatives, but failed to
persuade them to bring Elian with them to Washington to be
reunited with his father Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was hosted by Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin in Miami
Beach. An Associated Press report quoted her as saying that Reno
suggested the relatives fly to Washington Thursday for a meeting
with the boy's father.
</P>
<P>
However, the relatives in turn suggested that the father travel
to Florida for a meeting because of the illness of a family member.
</P>
<P>
The attorneys of the father and the Miami relatives will talk
by phone with Reno either late tonight or early Thursday morning,
O'Laughlin said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin
said in Washington that Reno is planning to work out a resolution,
trying to meet with the parties concerned to seek a cooperative
settlement in this case.
</P>
<P>
Marlin said Reno would meet with the Miami relatives who is
taking care of Elian and community leaders in Miami, where angry
Cuban exiles have vowed to prevent the boy's return to his father.
</P>
<P>
Carole Florman, a spokeswoman of the Justice Department, told
reporters that the department plans to send a letter later on
Wednesday on transferring Elian to his father from his Miami
relatives.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to encourage that the adults meet. At the same
time, we are moving forward with finalizing the letter which we
expect we will send by early afternoon unless other events make it
unnecessary," Florman said.
</P>
<P>
However, she added that even if the Justice Department sends
the letter instructing that the transfer occur at a specific date
and time, it could be changed later if the father and the boy's
Miami relatives reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
"We are not backing off the position that a transfer needs to
happen quickly," she said, stressing that a meeting between the
boy's Miami relatives and his father would be "desirable" if a
resolution can be reached.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gregory Craig, the attorney for Elian's father,
accused Lazaro Gonzalez, a great uncle of Elian, who is taking
custody of the boy in Miami, of backtracking on an agreement he
said they had reached on Tuesday to hand over the boy voluntarily
on Wednesday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"It is time for the Justice Department to instruct Lazaro
Gonzalez to follow the law and do the right thing. This son needs
his father," Craig told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He added that while the father had come to the United States
expecting to take custody of his child, he had now been here for a
week.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 last year after his mother and
other 11 people died when their boat capsized in the sea off
Florida. His relatives in Miami then took custody of him.
</P>
<P>
The relatives insists that the boy should remain in the United
States even after the boy's father came to the U.S. to pick up his
son.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Justice Department ruled earlier this year that the
boy belongs to his father and should be returned to Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
