<HEADLINE> IMF Predicts Recovery This Year in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 12 (Xinhua)- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) predicted a financial recovery this year for most Latin
American countries, although there still exists a potential for
vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
Recovery will be realized by the increase in domestic demand,
investments and exports, said an IMF report from Washington.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed anticipated improvements to policies
following recent crises, the introduction of solid structural
reforms and firm financial and fiscal procedures.
</P>
<P>
IMF said that in spite of the fact that many governments in
the region have reduced their tax deficits to attract foreign
investment, there still exists difficulty for them in gaining
international financing.
</P>
<P>
Possible assistance will be vital for some countries, like
Brazil and Argentina, whose financial needs exceed by 90 percent
the value of their exports, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The greatest negative factor for recovery in Latin America
comes from potentially unfavorable events in advanced countries'
economies, such as an eventual increase in interest rates in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The fragility of Latin American banking systems is another
factor contrary to the growth in production, which is expected to
rise by three percent this year, according to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The institution said that Brazil, Mexico, Argentina and
Colombia will register an account deficit of about 55 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Every School in Czech Republic to Have Internet Connections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Czech government Tuesday
decided that all elementary and middle schools and universities be
hooked to the Internet by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
The government will allocate 7 billion koruny (about 200
million U.S. dollars) in five years to attain such goals.
</P>
<P>
This was said here by Czech Education Minister Eduard Zeman who
added that there were two problems blocking Internet development
in the Czech Republic, namely the lack of money and qualified
professionals.
</P>
<P>
The Czech government's decision aims to shorten the gap between
the Czech Republic and western developed countries in information
technologies, he noted.
</P>
<P>
So far, only 81 percent of elementary and middle schools in the
country have access to the Internet. Many schools have no
computers, and they have no money for the application of the
Internet too. Still worse, most school teachers have little
knowledge about information technologies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
