<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mbeki: NAM Aims at Eradicating Poverty in Member Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Non-Aligned Movement (NAM)
Chairman Thabo Mbeki said Wednesday that the organization's
priorities are to eradicate poverty in all societies of its member
countries and to achieve sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who doubles as South Africa's president, made the
remark when he took the floor at the four-day South Summit, which
opened here Wednesday as the largest gathering of heads of state
and government from the Group of 77 (G-77) countries in its 36-
year history.
</P>
<P>
He told the gathering that the 113-nation NAM, founded in 1961
in the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade, is aimed at the permanent
elimination of poverty among its member countries and sustainable
improvement in the living standards of its peoples.
</P>
<P>
It also strives for "the enhancement of the dignity of our
peoples, which must include the protection of the environment in
which we live, respect for and defense of our languages and
cultures and the nurturing of the social cohesion of our
communities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Leaders and senior officials from 133 countries were
represented at the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
