<HEADLINE> Natural Gas Pipeline to be built between Panama, Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian thermo-electric company
Enron will build an underwater pipeline between Colombia and
Panama to provide natural gas to this Central American country's
thermoelectric companies.
</P>
<P>
Vice Minister of Panama's Domestic Trade, Ernesto Fernandez,
said Wednesday that the pipeline will help stabilize oil prices,
which often affect the power sector.
</P>
<P>
"With this, thermoelectric firms will be prevented from being
disadvantaged when fuel prices go up, as these run on diesel" he
said.
</P>
<P>
The 480-kilometer pipeline, which runs between Cartagena,
Colombia and Colon, Panama, will be constructed in three stages in
18 months, at a cost of 360 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the company hasn't set the date to start the project,
Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the pipeline will also benefit the industrial
sector in the Panama Canal zone for domestic usage and
transportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
