<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Military Maps on Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-seven military maps drawn
by the Japanese troops during their invasion in northeast China
confirm once again the iron-clad fact of Japanese invasion of
China during the World War II.
</P>
<P>
Xun Xinwu, an 82-year-old resident in Harbin, northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province, discovered the maps on the site of the
Japanese troops command in the city after they retreated.
</P>
<P>
All the railway lines, roads, and the deployment of the Chinese
warships on the Songhua River were marked explicitly in both
Japanese and Chinese. And most of the names of cities, mountains,
and rivers in the maps were more or less the same with today's.
</P>
<P>
"The maps tell almost everything about the topography and
mineral resources there and show the strategy of Japanese military
troops in northeast China," said Cheng Penghan, research fellow in
the Northeast Memorial to Martyrs.
</P>
<P>
Xun decided to turn in all the maps to the local government as
he heard that Azuma Shiro, a former Japanese soldier was convicted
in a Japanese court for telling the truth about the war crimes
committed by Japanese troops.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China-Russia Railway Line Good for Northeast Asia Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Another railway line has opened
linking Hunchun in northeast China's Jilin Province and Makhalino
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
The new line will boost the economy in the Tumen River Delta
area, where China, Russia, and the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea meet, and accelerate cooperation and exchange among the
northeast Asian countries, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
The railway line will make it easier and faster for China to
transport cargo to Japan, Republic of Korea, and North America by
first transporting them to the Russian ports through Makhalino
station.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program allocated 30 billion U.S.
dollars in 1991 for the Tumen River Project, with the aim to set
up another international cargo transportation hub, and an trading
and processing center in northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
China has invested more than 4 billion yuan (about 480 million
U.S. dollars) in the Project for infrastructure construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
