<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Study New Trends to Protect Patents, Copyrights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Areas protected by patents and
copyright systems should be expanded, officials and experts with
the State Intellectual Property Office (SIPO) said at a symposium
in Beijing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, scheduled to close today, was jointly sponsored by
SIPO and the Intellectual Property Department of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Yin Xintian, director of the Legal Affairs Department under the
SIPO, said that SIPO was studying new trends appearing in the
United States and Japan to protect more items, including creative
business ideas, with patent systems.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 officials, experts and scholars from the Chinese
mainland, Hong Kong and Macao took part in the symposium.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the importance of intellectual property,
experts warned that inventions and creations should not be
protected at the cost of curbing rapid science and technology
developments.
</P>
<P>
The latest development of patent protections, new methods to
deal with intellectual property disputes, and publicizing
intellectual property knowledge were also discussed at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Selby, director of the HKSAR's Intellectual Property
Departments, said the intellectual property system must be
adjusted to meet the challenges of globalization and the fast
development of information technologies.
</P>
<P>
A large-scale education campaign was also performed in Hong
Kong, Selby said, adding that the mainland should intensify its
mass education to increase public awareness of intellectual
property protections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
