<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Celebrates Traditional New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A two-day public holiday to mark the new year begins on
Thursday. Thousands of people left the city for their villages or
towns to celebrate the new year.
</P>
<P>
The whole country, especially rural areas, is reverberated with
beating of drums and lighting of fire crackers.
</P>
<P>
The cooking of milk rice, the wearing of new cloths, greetings
to the elders in the family and the feeling of friendship towards
all,are common to both the Sinhalese and Tamil people.
</P>
<P>
However, the Sri Lankan troops and police have tightened
security in the whole country, particularly in the capital city
Colombo, during the new year in bid to prevent possible attacks of
the Tamil rebels who have been fighting a war since 1983 against
the government for a separate Tamil state in the country.
</P>
<P>
The troops and police have launched a joint search operations
against the rebels in Colombo and its suburbs during the past
three days.
</P>
<P>
" What should absorb all our efforts and receive our highest
priority in the new year is the definite ending of the terrorism
that has engulfed our country and society in two decades of the
worst tragedy our people have seen", said Sri Lankan president
Chandrika Kumaratunga in her new year message to the nation.
</P>
<P>
She said to achieve this all important goal it is necessary to
unite with the singular commitment to overcome the forces of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
On the new year, "let us all make a firm resolution to
strengthen and develop thinking and action that will lead us to a
new dawn, fresh with the rays of hope for a peaceful land", the
President added in her message. 
</P>
</TEXT>
