<HEADLINE> Reno Arrives in Miami to Settle Dispute on Cuban Boy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno arrived in Miami Wednesday to help settle a dispute over the
custody of 6-year-old Cuban shipwreck survivor Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Washington earlier on Wednesday,
Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin said that Reno is
planning to work out a cooperative settlement and meeting with the
parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
Marlin said Reno would meet with the Miami relatives who are
taking care of Elian and community leaders in Miami, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
Carole Florman, a spokeswoman for the Justice Department, told
reporters that the department plans to send a letter on Wednesday
to Elian's Miami relatives on his transfer to his father.
</P>
<P>
"We are encouraging the adults to meet. At the same time, we
are moving forward with finalizing the letter, which we expect we
will send by early afternoon unless other events make it
unnecessary," Florman said.
</P>
<P>
However, she added that even if the Justice Department sends
the letter instructing the transfer occur at a specific date and
time, it could be changed if the father and the boy's Miami
relatives reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
"We are not backing off the position that a transfer needs to
happen quickly," she said, stressing that a meeting between the
boy's Miami relatives and his father would be "desirable" if a
resolution can be reached.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gregory Craig, the attorney for Elian's father,
accused Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great uncle who is taking custody
of the boy in Miami, of backtracking on an agreement he said they
had reached on Tuesday to hand the boy over voluntarily on
Wednesday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"It is time for the Justice Department to instruct Lazaro
Gonzalez to follow the law and do the right thing. This son needs
his father," Craig told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He added that while the father had come to the United States
expecting to take custody of his child, he has now been here for a
week.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 last year after his mother and
other 11 people died when their boat capsized in the Atlantic off
Florida. His relatives in Miami then took custody of him.
</P>
<P>
The relatives insist that the boy should remain in the United
States even after the boy's father came to the U.S. to pick him up.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Justice Department ruled earlier this year that the
boy belongs to his father and should be returned to Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
