<HEADLINE> NAM Chairman on Principles in North-South Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The eradication of poverty and the
attainment of sustainable development in the South calls for "a
constructive and purposeful relationship" between the developed
North and the developing South, Thabo Mbeki, Chairman of the Non-
Aligned Movement (NAM), said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Speedy movement forward towards their accomplishment requires
a constructive and purposeful relationship between ourselves and
the countries of the North," Mbeki said at the four-day South
Summit of the Group of 77 (G-77) that opened here.
</P>
<P>
The summit, the largest gathering of heads of state and
government from 133 countries since the founding of G-77 in 1964,
is focused on the North-South relations and the South-South
cooperation among major topics.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who doubles as South Africa's president, noted that a
sound North-South relationship should be based on the alleviation
of debt, guarantee of effective capital flows into developing
countries, and transfer of technology to the South.
</P>
<P>
It must address "the alleviation of the debt burden carried by
many of our countries, including its cancellation, an effective
mechanism to ensure a substantial increase in capital flows into
the developing economies as this is a prerequisite for development,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said, "if the technology divide between the North and
South grows in the wake of rapid advances in communication and bio-
technology, then all will suffer and not just the developing world.
"
</P>
<P>
The North-South relationship should also cover "the reversal of
the trend resulting in a sharp drop in official development
assistance, and the opening of the markets of the developed
countries to our products, including agricultural products, "
Mbeki added.
</P>
<P>
The NAM leader urged the developing countries to step up
cooperation, saying, "we are faced with the challenge to reinforce
the interaction and exchanges among ourselves as the countries of
the South, to strengthen South-South cooperation."
</P>
<P>
NAM, founded in 1961 in the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade,
currently groups 113 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
