<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> America's Young Adults Turning to Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Internet is quickly
displacing older media, such as television and newspapers as the
prime source of important information for the U.S.'s young adults,
according to survey results released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A nationwide telephone poll of more than 1,000 households
commissioned by the Round Table Group (RTG), a U.S. consulting
firm of university professors, said that 67 percent of Americans
aged 18-24 live in households that use the Internet to gather key
information, compared to a nationwide average of just 46 percent
who use the Internet for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
Among those young adults, 59 percent say their households
currently receive more "useful information" from Internet than
from newspapers. Fifty-three percent say they receive more "useful
information" from the Internet than from television.
</P>
<P>
"Traditional media has a right to feel fearful of these rapidly
changing demographics," said RTG CEO Russ Rosenzweig. "The
changeover is happening much more rapidly than anyone predicted."
</P>
<P>
According to the study, 84 percent of young adult Internet
users say their families are more likely to use the Internet to
retrieve useful information than they are likely to go to the
public library, and 68 percent of the those households are more
likely to consult some specific questions on the Internet than
turn to a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-three percent of Internet households in the 18-24 age
group say they have used the Internet to retrieve work-related
information. And 47 percent of that age group say that someone in
their household would probably be interested in taking an
educational course over the Internet for work or for other
purposes.
</P>
<P>
The study found the slowest groups to log onto the Internet
have been the elderly, the poor and those with the least education.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. broadcast executives went on the offensive
against those who predict the imminent death of traditional radio
and television. Speaking at the ongoing annual convention of the
National Association of Broadcasters (NAB) in Las Vegas, NAB chief
executive Eddie Fritts said that "broadcasting stands before a
door that is opening, not one that is closing."
</P>
<P>
Executives from newspapers, magazines and other traditional
media also said that the Internet was changing traditional media,
but not replacing them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0303 </DOCNO>
