<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Oil, Gas Production Drops in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar produced a total of 3.394
million barrels of crude oil and 1.673 billion cubic-meters of
natural gas in 1999, respectively dropping by 0.8 percent and 4.34
percent compared with 1998, according to the latest figures of the
country's Central Statistical Organization.
</P>
<P>
So far, Myanmar's petroleum and its products are insufficient
to meet the demand and the country still has to import 280,000 to
300,000 tons of crude oil and 100,000 to 150,000 tons of diesel
oil annually.
</P>
<P>
Since Myanmar opened to foreign investment in late 1988,foreign
investment in the oil and gas sector coming from Australia,
Britain, France, Indonesia, Japan, Thailand and the United States
has reached 2.3 billion U.S. dollars in 46 projects, accounting
for 32.39 percent of the 7.1 billion dollars' total foreign
investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Less Foreign Tourists Visit Myanmar in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Myanmar annually earns only over 30 million U.S. dollars from
tourism.
</P>
<P>
There is a total of 492 hotels in Myanmar with 13,984 rooms.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the Asian financial crisis, Myanmar's tourism
business has been poor with the majority of its hotel rooms
remaining unoccupied.
</P>
<P>
The country targets to draw 500,000 foreign tourists annually.
</P>
<P>
Since Myanmar opened to foreign investment in late 1988, it has
absorbed 1.112 billion dollars of investment in the sector of
hotels and tourism in 31 projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
