<HEADLINE> Food Guarantee Challenges Latin America in 21st Century: Mexican President  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo said Wednesday that one of the greatest challenges to
Latin America and the Caribbean in the 21st century is to
guarantee enough food for their population.
</P>
<P>
"The scourge of hunger coming about in countries with great
economical setbacks isn't acceptable," Zedillo said in his
opening speech at FAO's 26th Regional Conference in the city of
Merida, southeast Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural ministers and experts from 33 countries in the
region are attending this forum, whose preparatory meetings began
April 10 and will end April 14 in Merida, 960 kilometers southeast
of Mexico City, capital of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to a document from United Nations for Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO), the number of people suffering
from malnutrition in Latin America went down in recent years from
58.6 million to 53.4 million, although it increased in the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo described FAO as a first-rate instrument for facing the
food challenge by coordinating actions between governments and
societies.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the tragedy happening in Ethiopia, Zediilo said
the situation there is "very sad". He urged more assistance to the
Horn of Africa country which has been hit hardly by drought.
</P>
<P>
FAO General Director, Senegalese Jacques Diouf, exhorted
countries in the region to intensify their efforts of pressing for
a thorough fight against hunger and poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
