<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wine Named after Tavern in Literature Sells Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- "Xianheng," the trademark of
rice wine produced by a company in Shaoxing in eastern Zhejiang
Province, has been evaluated as worth more than 154 million yuan,
as the name originates from the novels of prestigious Chinese
revolutionary writer Lu Xun (1881-1936).
</P>
<P>
In Lu's novels "Kong Yiji" and "Medicine," Xianheng is the name
of a little tavern in Shaoxing, his hometown.
</P>
<P>
Rice wine produced by the company is selling well both at home
and abroad, and Zhang Shangming, general manger of the Zhejiang
Xianheng Industrial Group, attributes the booming business to the
name "Xianheng," which he said could not only reflect the history
of Shaoxing wine, but also has a great association with important
Chinese literature.
</P>
<P>
The company has patented the trademark in China and some foreign
countries including the Republic of Korea, Japan, Singapore, and
Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
