<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China News Digest: West on the Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China has adopted a strategy of
developing its vast western part, making it a key task in the
national economy this year and in coming years. The central
government and all provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities have taken substantial steps to implement the
central government strategy. Following are major stories on the
development in the western regions this week.
</P>
<P>
East-West Seeks Win-Win Cooperation
</P>
<P>
The five-day Investment and Trade Fair for Cooperation Between
East and West China closed on Sunday, clinching contracts worth
100 billion yuan (12 billion U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The combined value of contracts and investment signed at the
fair was 2.5 times more than the previous session. Over 60 percent
of the contracts were infrastructure, high-tech and tourism
contracts.
</P>
<P>
Jia Zhibang, vice-governor of Shaanxi Province, described the
fair as a win-win cooperation between east and west China under
the strategy of accelerating economic development in western China.
</P>
<P>
China Steps up Fiscal Transfer to Western Areas
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is promoting fiscal transfer as a major
financial support to accelerate development of the enormous
western territory.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Finance Jin Liqun said here on Monday that
fiscal transfer will become the major channel for facilitating
development of west China, as the short-term pro-active fiscal
policy is going to be phased out.
</P>
<P>
China now is funding projects in the west with money earned
from treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
China to Build First Cross-Desert Expressway
</P>
<P>
China is to build the country's first cross-desert expressway
in Shaanxi Province, as part of the efforts to implement the
central government's strategy to boost the economy of western
China.
</P>
<P>
The expressway will stretch from Yulin City to Jingbian County,
cutting across the 10,000 sq km Mu Us Desert, on the borders of
Shaanxi and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The 118-km-long expressway is expected to cost 1.9 billion yuan.
Early-stage preparations have been completed, and construction has
commenced on certain sections. Its upper speed limit will be 100
kph.
</P>
<P>
East China to Get More Electricity From West
</P>
<P>
China is trying to tap the huge power resources in its western
regions in a bid to provide more electricity for energy-short
eastern China.
</P>
<P>
Hydropower resources in west China tops 270 million kw,
accounting for about 72 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
China's strategy of transmitting electricity from west to east
is of significance for improving the country's energy structure
and ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
Provinces and cities in east China should provide more markets
for electricity transmitted from the west by speeding up the
readjustment of energy structure and closing down small thermal
power plants. The west should improve its investment environment
to ensure adequate power supply to the east.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
