<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laid-off Do-gooder Applies for Guinness Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A 52-year-old man is applying for
entry into the world record book for his good deeds over the past
38 years.
</P>
<P>
Shen Yongbin, a laid-off worker in Harbin in northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province, began to help others in 1962 when he
rescued a boy who fell into the water in the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Since then he has done 130 good deeds, he says, including
collecting anti-flood signatures in 1998, participating in long-
distance running to commemorate the return of Hong Kong and Macao,
and posting telephone numbers for the public good at his own
expense.
</P>
<P>
Shen has had his good deed notarized and is ready to apply for
confirmation by the Shanghai Office of the Guinness Book of World
Record.
</P>
<P>
On March 5, 1963, late Chinese Chairman Mao Zedong called on
the whole nation to learn from Lei Feng, a soldier who was always
ready to help others and died in 1962 at the age of 22.
</P>
<P>
Shen's decision has stirred some argument. Some believe he is
only fishing for fame and compliments, because Lei Feng never
boasted of what he had done for others. But others support Shen
for his good deeds, saying there is nothing shameful about it at
all.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
