<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru President Vote Goes to Runoff: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 12 (Xinhua) - Peru's presidential election will go
to a runoff between Alberto Fujimori, who fell just short of re-
election, and Alejandro Toledo, the National Election Office said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jose Portillo, head of the election office said with 97.68
percent of the ballots counted and Fujimori having 49.84 percent
of the valid votes, the results could not now change enough to
push the incumbent president past the mark of 50 percent of valid
votes that is needed for an outright win.
</P>
<P>
"The results could be changed by five hundredths of a decimal
point of valid votes, which means there would be no change," he
said, adding that Fujimori can finish no higher than 49.89 percent.
</P>
<P>
 Toledo, who won 40.31 percent of the vote, will face Fujimori
in a second round scheduled for early June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
