<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Social Work Education Develops Rapidly in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Social work has become a hot
specialty in many Chinese universities and polytechnic schools in
recent years, according to a meeting held in this capital city of
east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 30 schools of higher learning and a dozen
polytechnic schools in the country offer majors in the field,
enrolling some 3,000 students annually.
</P>
<P>
Ten more universities and colleges are applying to open this
concentration, it was announced at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Teaching of social work was introduced in China in the 1920s
from western countries, but was eliminated from college
curriculums in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
In the years that followed, China operated under a planned
economic system under through which government organizations and
various work units, especially the civil affairs departments at
all levels, were responsible for resolving social problems and
helping needy people.
</P>
<P>
With the progress of China's economic reform since the late
1970s, it became necessary to develop social work education.
</P>
<P>
In 1986 China's education authorities gave approval to Beijing
University to add a social work and management major to the
curriculum. In 1993, the China Youth Political College became the
first college in the Chinese mainland to form a department of
social work and management.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the 1990s, the country's reforms have
produced numerous social problems such as increasing redundant
workers, surplus rural workers pouring into cities, a sharp rise
in the number of single-parent families, and the growing aging
population.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of social work education just epitomizes
these changes, social scientists here noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Customs Cracks Down On Frozen Meat Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The smuggling of frozen meat
into China has increased since the beginning of the year, as the
country tightens quarantines on imported meat to keep out
livestock with vesicular disease.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou Customs in south China's Guangdong Province seized
700 tons of smuggled frozen meat in the first three months, and
customs officials told Xinhua that the smuggling is mixed into
general trade, which includes frozen chicken, pork, and beef.
</P>
<P>
Customs authorities in Guangdong handles the largest imports of
fresh and frozen meat in China, and more than 1,200 tons of
smuggled frozen meat worth 8.67 million yuan (about one million US
dollars) have been detected at the customs since last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts said people who eat the smuggled meat have greater risk
of contracting vesicular disease, which was detected in livestock
in the Republic of Korea and Japan this year. The disease, which
is better known as hoof-and-mouth disease, is highly communicable
and is as harmful to human beings as to animals.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration for Entry-Exit Inspection and
Quarantine has banned direct imports of frozen meat from the ROK
and Japan since April 3, and Guangzhou Customs has pledged to
mount a continuing fight against smuggling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
