<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Stroke Control Center Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-U.S. stroke control center
was recently established in Qingdao, a coastal city in east China'
s Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The International Stroke Control Center, jointly funded by the
University of Wisconsin of the United States and a military
hospital in Qingdao, concentrates on the prevention and cure of
strokes.
</P>
<P>
The center advocates a type of surgery in which plaques are
removed from a patient's carotid artery, which is believed to
restrict blood flow to the heart and cause strokes.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.5 million Chinese suffer strokes annually, and two
thirds of them die.
</P>
<P>
More than 700,000 stroke patients in the United States have
undergone the plaque-removal surgery; 100,000 of them were
patients at the medical school of the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
