<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2300GMT, Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEL AVIV -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin arrived here Wednesday
for a state visit to Israel at the invitation of Israeli President
Ezer Weizman. 
</P>
<P>
This is the first visit by a Chinese head of state to the
country. During his visit, Jiang is expected to exchange views with
Israeli leaders on major international and regional issues of
common concern. (Israel-China)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid on
Wednesday lashed out at an Israeli decision to expand settlement on
the Golan Heights as "a provocative act" that will obstruct the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said in a statement that the construction of new
housing units on the strategic plateau that Israel captured from
Syria in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war "blocks the windows" of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel said on Tuesday that it had approved the building of 200
more homes on the Golan as it foresaw no early resumption of
negotiations with Damascus on the return of the heights. (Arab
League-Israel-Golan Settlement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's prison authority announced Wednesday that
13 of the 15 Lebanese detainees now in its custody will be set free
by the start of next week.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was issued following an ruling of Israel's
Supreme Court earlier in the day, which ordered immediately release
of eight of the detainees because they have been illegally kept for
years as bargaining chips for missing Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
In the ruling reached by a nine-judge panel with a 6-3 vote, the
court said Israeli law does not give Israeli defense ministry the
authority to hold these Lebanese citizens in administrative
detention as they are not presenting threats to the security of the
country. (Israel-Lebanon-Detainees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman held a ceremony here
Wednesday to welcome Chinese President Jiang Zemin, who is paying a
state visit to Israel.
</P>
<P>
In his welcome speech, Weizman hailed Jiang's visit as a
historic one, noting that this is the first time that a Chinese
president pays a visit to Israel.
</P>
<P>
This visit will surely "lay a foundation for the deepening of
relations between Israel and China," Weizman said. (Israel-China-
Jiang-Ceremony)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin said here
Wednesday that China and Israel, both having misfortunes in the
past, hope to live in a peaceful environment in the new century.
</P>
<P>
The two countries each has a long history and made outstanding
contributions to the progress of human civilization, Jiang said
during his meeting with Israeli President Ezer Weizman.
</P>
<P>
He expressed appreciation for the hospitality shown by the
Israeli people to his current state visit.
</P>
<P>
Weizman expressed his warm welcome to Jiang, saying that Israel
has been looking forward to Jiang's visit for a long time. (Israel-
China-Jiang-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin here
Wednesday expressed his hope that confrontation will come to an
end, disputes be settled and hostilities be removed in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a welcoming dinner hosted by Israeli President Ezer
Weizman, Jiang said he hoped that concerted efforts will be made so
that all the countries in the region will be able to concentrate on
economic and cultural undertakings and all the peoples there will
enjoy a peaceful and better life.
</P>
<P>
He said that to settle the Middle East question at an early date
is the unshirkable historical responsibility of the peoples of all
countries in the region, as well as all the peace-loving and
progressive people in the world. (Israel-Jiang's Speech-Middle
East)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin on Wednesday
called for joint efforts of the people of all countries to
establish a fair and equitable new international political and
economic order.
</P>
<P>
The Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence, the purposes and
principles of the U.N. Charter and other universally recognized
norms governing international relations, far from being outdated,
should constitute the basis of the new order, Jiang said at the
welcoming dinner hosted by Israeli President Ezer Weizman.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to put into practice the principles of mutual
respect for sovereignty and territorial integrity, mutual non-
aggression, non-interference in each other's internal affairs,
Jiang said. (Israel-Jiang's Speech-New World Order) 
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman Wednesday called on
China to play a more important role in promoting the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We expect China, a very important and responsible country which
aims at peace and stability in the world and has good relations
with all the countries in the Middle East, to assist in encouraging
the process," Weizman said at a dinner in honor of visiting Chinese
President Jiang Zemin. (Israel-China-Weizman) 
</P>
</TEXT>
