<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lewis Stripped of WBA Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- British boxer Lennox Lewis has
been stripped of his World Boxing Association belt, meaning he is
no longer the undisputed heavyweight champion of the world.
</P>
<P>
According to the BBC report, New York judge Lewis Kaplan
declared the title vacant Wednesday and ordered Lewis to hand back
the belt immediately.
</P>
<P>
The decision is the result of a row between the British fighter
's camp and American promoter Don King over who the first defense
of the title should be against.
</P>
<P>
Panos Eliades, Lewis's promoter, said: "It's a bloody liberty,
and I'm preparing to appeal against what is a diabolical decision.
</P>
<P>
"They tried to rob us in the ring in New York last March when
Lennox was adjudged to have only drawn with Evander Holyfield, and
now they have succeeded. In my view, the judge is totally
incompetent, but we will fight on. The battle isn't over yet," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Lennox is very disappointed, although he still has the WBC and
IBF belts," he added.
</P>
<P>
The row centers around a proviso in Lewis's deal when he fought
Evander Holyfield for the second time last year to earn his
undisputed title.
</P>
<P>
It said that Lewis's first defense of his WBA belt would be
against the number one contender, Henry Akinwande, who is managed
by King.
</P>
<P>
Failing that, it should be against the highest-rated available
contender. But it has since been revealed that Akinwande has
hepatitis B and Lewis refused to fight him on health grounds.
</P>
<P>
He signed to fight Michael Grant instead on 29 April in New
York, when both the WBC and IBF belts will be at stake.
</P>
<P>
The WBA sanctioned this fight, but King was unhappy about it
and asked that Lewis be stripped of the title.
</P>
<P>
Frank Maloney, Lewis's manager said: "To lose a title in a
courtroom when you've been chasing one for 10 years is a real
knockout blow and a huge disappointment for boxing. But the real
fans know who the champion of the world is." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA President Snubs Leeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- European soccer governing body
UEFA president Lennart Johanssen said on Wednesday that Turkish
fans should be allowed to travel to Leeds for the second-leg of
their UEFA Cup semi-final match.
</P>
<P>
The British club has called for a ban on Galatasaray supporters,
following the murder of two Leeds fans in Istanbul, prior to last
week's first-leg.
</P>
<P>
Feelings are running high in the city and the Leeds United
board,after consultations with the Football Association and West
Yorkshire Police, have voiced concerns about the safety of any
travelling fans.
</P>
<P>
Johannsen said: "There are Turks all over Europe and one way or
another they will see to it they get a ticket for the match. So in
many respects it's wishful thinking from Leeds to play just in
front of their home fans."
</P>
<P>
"I think the Turkish supporters are also shocked about the
events in Istanbul. I predict there will be absolutely no problem,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
He also added that incidents outside stadiums were often beyond
the control of the governing body and the delay in making the
decision, which is now due on Thursday, was down to the complexity
of the arguments being considered.
</P>
<P>
UEFA has received written submissions from Leeds, the Football
Association and the relevant local and national security
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Galatasaray will now be given a chance to respond. Once its
report has been submitted, UEFA will decide whether to switch the
tie to a neutral venue.
</P>
<P>
Leeds chairman Peter Ridsdale has hinted his club may pull out
of the competition if UEFA choose a neutral venue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
