<HEADLINE> Tyson May Fight in Scotland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- American controversial boxer Mike
Tyson could be on the verge of agreeing to fight in Scotland after
his promoters visited the national stadium, Hampden Park.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Frank Warren's Sports Network company
travelled to Glasgow, with a view to staging Tyson's next fight at
the revamped stadium.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Scottish Football Association, which has
taken over the running of the debt-ridden stadium, said: "Hampden
was visited over a possible staging of a Mike Tyson fight. This is
at a very early stage and no details, including any possible dates,
have even been discussed yet."
</P>
<P>
He added: "We are waiting to hear back from the promoters."
</P>
<P>
In January the former undisputed heavyweight world champion
defeated Britain's Julius Francis in front of 22,000 fans at the
Manchester Evening News Arena in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
But critics said the boxer should not have been allowed into
the country due to his conviction for rape in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Tyson, who created a storm of criticism when he bit the ear of
his opponent Evander Holyfield in 1997, is set to face Lou
Saverese in Milan on 20 May.
</P>
<P>
Ibrox stadium, home of Glasgow Rangers Football Club, was also
in the running to stage the fighter's next bout, but was ruled out
when a suitable date could not be found.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Sports Network said: "We looked at Hampden and
it is one of a number of other venues around Europe that are being
checked out." 
</P>
</TEXT>
