<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100 GMT, Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The first session of the closed-door trial on 13
Iranian Jews accused of spying for Iran's arch foes of the United
States and Israel was adjourned Thursday and postponed to May 1.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Ali Amiri, head of the justice department of the
southern Fars province, said the trial was put off upon the request
of a defense lawyer, though the accused had announced readiness for
defense.
</P>
<P>
He said the court made the decision with respect to the ideology
of the Jews and views of the accused that the timing of the trial
coincided with the Jewish feast of Passover, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported. (Iran-Jews-Trial-Adjourned)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli government on Thursday lifted a ban on
construction on the Golan Heights, a move that might harm the
Israeli-Syrian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Yossi Kucik, a confidant of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and director general of his office, announced Thursday that all
construction and development plans on the Golan will be given the
go-ahead from now on. (Israel-Golan Heights)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin said here
Thursday that China cherishes its traditional friendship and
mutually beneficial cooperation with Israel and appreciates the
importance Israeli government attached to China.
</P>
<P>
"China would like to join hands with Israel to push forward the
mutually beneficial bilateral cooperation," Jiang said during his
meeting with Avraham Burg, speaker of the Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that the Israeli parliament should play a
positive role in promoting the Sino-Israeli ties. (Israel-China-
Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said Thursday that
there is great potential for the development of Sino-Israeli ties,
and the two sides should join hands in expanding mutually
beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He made this remark at a meeting with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Although China and Israel are different in terms of domestic
situation, development levels and population and size, Jiang said,
they share the aspiration of speeding up the development of
bilateral ties. (Israel-China-Jiang-Barak)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin expressed his
conviction here Thursday that leaders in the Middle East have
wisdom and courage to realize the "peace of the brave" in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak during their
meeting Thursday afternoon that it is natural that there are
difficulties and obstacles in the present negotiations on the
Middle East peace, but the difficulties can be overcome.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed his appreciation for the efforts Barak has made
for re-launching the peace negotiations since he took office last
July. (Israel-Jiang-Barak-Peace Process)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin's first state visit
to Israel is a historic event in the relations between Israel and
China, said Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak here Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Speaking a dinner he hosted in honor of the Chinese president,
Barak said both Israel and China are ancient countries in the world
with rich culture and civilization and the Israeli government
attaches great importance to the development of friendly relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation in various fields between the two countries has
a bright future and the Israeli government will continue to strive
hard to further enhance such cooperation in the future for the
benefits of the two peoples, Barak said. (Israel-China-Barak-Jiang)
</P>
