<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia: UNSCOM Staff Who Abused Their Positions to be excluded in UNMOVIC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Sergei Lavrov, Russia's
Ambassador to the United Nations, stressed on Thursday that his
country wanted to make sure no personnel from the United Nations
Special Commission(UNSCOM) who had abused their positions would be
included in the new U.N. arms regime for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the United Nations Security Council
this morning approved the organizational plan presented by Hans
Blix, Executive Chairman of the United Nations Monitoring,
Verification and Inspection Commission(UNMOVIC) which was created
by U.N. resolution 1284 to replace now defunct UNSCOM, for this
new arms regime.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Lavrov said Iraq's cooperation with the
United Nations would depend on how U.N. resolution 1284 would be
implemented and whether criteria for a suspension of sanctions
against the country would be clarified.
</P>
<P>
Unilateral actions, such as U.S.-British daily bombing raids
over air exclusive zones would continue to hamper compliance, and
the exclusive zones were not authorized by the Security Council,
Lavrov said.
</P>
<P>
"To see this resolution implemented, we need all to be within
decisions of the Security Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador said he would prefer to see a stronger political
and legal component which would allow the commission to solve
potential crises as they start working in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said Richard Butler, Executive Chairman of UNSCOM, in the
past did not really try to solve problems but would always run to
the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council which was formally
presented early this week, Hans Blix recommended that UNMOVIC be
strong on experts and technical personnel rather than political
functionaries. He has not decided the new inspectors for UNMOVIC.
</P>
<P>
U.N. arms inspection in Iraq has been suspended since the U.S.-
led military strikes against the country in December 1998. Iraq so
far has refused to accept Resolution 1284,saying lifting sanctions
is the precondition for U.N. arms inspectors to return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
