<HEADLINE> South Countries Tied to Up-to-date Technology : G-77 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The heads of state of the Group of 77 (G-77) met at Havana,
continued on Thursday their debates on the most important issues
related to the South countries situation, among which is access to
up-to-date technology by the South.
</P>
<P>
It is known that modern technology allows the income of
millions of U.S. dollars in investment capital and the creation of
advanced industries.
</P>
<P>
World Trade Organization's figures show that computer and
telecommunications technology advances give great advantages to
North countries.
</P>
<P>
According to these data, 88 percent of all the Internet users
are located in industrial nations, while the 10 top transnational
business control 70 percent of the computers industry, and up to
86 percent of the telecommunications industry. Of these companies,
not one has its headquarters in the South.
</P>
<P>
The World Trade Organization admitted that 1999 was a bad year
for raw material exporting nations, basically in the South, due to
the price fall, which affects capital investment attraction to
acquire up-to-date technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
