<HEADLINE> South Summit Debates over Debt, Trade and Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Foreign debt condonation, free
trade access to North markets and a further development of South-
South cooperation are some of the issues that had more attention
on Thursday by Third World leaders gathered at Havana.
</P>
<P>
Some twenty heads of state spoke on Wednesday before the
committee of the whole of the Group of 77 (G-77), and a similar
amount of participants was expected to speak to participate on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting taking place in the Conventions Palace, at Havana,
will be over on Friday, with the signing of the Havana Declaration
and the approval of the Action Program containing those projects
aimed at developing South-South cooperation for the years to come.
</P>
<P>
Opinions related to foreign debts are unanimous in the sense
that countries with few resources must receive a special treatment,
and this way, some leaders have pledged for foreign debt immediate
cancellation.
</P>
<P>
Those African heads of state who spoke on Thursday said that
Sub-Saharan countries' foreign debt has increased threefold during
the last 20 years, which translates to 350 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Regarding to foreign trade, there participated many speakers,
among them United Nations' Secretary- General Kofi Annan, insisted
in saying that industrialized countries should allow unrestricted
access to products from developing countries to their markets.
</P>
<P>
About South-South cooperation there were different points of
view by the different participants in the forum, yet a common
denominator was that there still exist unexplored potentials that
would allow a more effective cooperation among developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
As a proposal to oil exporting countries, Cuba's President,
Fidel Castro, suggested there should be a different oil price
system for the world's poor nations so that they are able to face
price increases without the need to further indebt their economies.
</P>
<P>
Another issue that was present all along, was that of armed
conflicts come to an end, and a reduction in military expenditure
as fundamentals to improve confidence among Third World countries
and the alleviation of their harmed economies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
