<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moore Supports China's Accession to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- World Trade Organization
Director-General Mike Moore said here Thursday that China's
accession to the global trade body would not be affected by U.S.
decision on permanent normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
"If the U.S. decided that it would not extend PNTR with China,
it is possible that China joins the WTO without U.S. approval,"
Moore said in a speech at the National Press Club in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"This is an organization of all its members, and at that point,
the U.S. will lose a lot of opportunities that it has helped
create through its negotiations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's overwhelmingly in the interests of U.S. businesses and
workers that China joins the WTO," he said.
</P>
<P>
Warning the U.S. Congress against rejecting the Clinton
administration's trade agreement with China, Moore said the U.S.
risked losing the benefits of the agreement if Congress rejects
permanent normal trade relations (PNTR) with China.
</P>
<P>
If Congress rejected the trade pact, Moore said, U.S.businesses
may not receive the same trade benefits as other WTO members.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House and Senate are expected to vote on the PNTR
legislation in late May and in the first week of June respectively.
</P>
<P>
Moore also spoke highly of China's economic reform and opening
to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
"Never before in history has one country lifted so many of its
people from poverty," he said. "A policy of greater openness in
China has been instrumental in lifting 120 million people out of
extreme poverty over the past 20 years."  
</P>
</TEXT>
