<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0370 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF: Marine Turtles Faces Danger of Extinction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Despite decades of conservation
efforts, six of the world's seven species of marine turtle are
still in danger of extinction, the World Wide Fund (WWF) warned in
a new publication issued here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In its report, 'Wanted Alive! Marine Turtles in the Wild', the
conservation organization emphasized that threats such as over-use
mean that no population of marine turtle can be considered
completely safe, even when currently stable as a result of long
term conservation and management.
</P>
<P>
Despite the precarious state of the species, WWF said, Cuba and
Dominica have proposed that the Convention on the Trade in
Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) reopen the
international trade in tortoiseshell coming almost exclusively
from the critically endangered Hawksbill turtle.
</P>
<P>
"We shouldn't be reopening the trade because controls in the
main importing country, Japan, are inadequate, the status of the
turtle populations in the Caribbean is unclear, and regional
management is patchy," said Elizabeth Kemf, Species Information
Manager at WWF, and co-author of the report. "Hawksbills, like
other marine turtles are facing ever growing numbers of threats."
</P>
<P>
Turtles all around the globe are hunted for their shells which
are used in jewelry, and their hides which are cured for leather,
according to WWF.
</P>
<P>
WWF estimated that up to 300,000 turtles are killed each year
as 'bycatch' in trawling nets, shrimp nets and longlines for tuna
and swordfish.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is also a major threat to turtles, said the
conservation organization. The construction of seawalls, hotels,
marinas and the entire infrastructure associated with coastal
tourism and commerce have destroyed large areas of turtle nesting
beaches around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0371 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Stronger South-South Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China said here Thursday that it
is particularly imperative and urgent for developing countries to
carry forward the spirit of solidarity and enhance the South-South
cooperation at a time when they are faced with common challenges.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing, head of
the Chinese Government delegation, took the floor at the first
South Summit of the Group of 77 since its founding in 1964.
</P>
<P>
"The South-South cooperation is, first and foremost, a
solidarity spirit," he said. "It is also an important way for
developing countries to seek greater strength and pursue common
development."
</P>
<P>
The founding of the Group of 77 more than three decades ago
significantly symbolizes this important solidarity spirit and is
of great importance and far-reaching influence, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since then, developing countries have spoken in one voice in
the international political and economic arena, fought
unremittingly for their legitimate rights and interests as one
strong force and made a remarkable contribution to the efforts to
change the irrational international political and economic order,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is particularly imperative and urgent for us to carry
forward the spirit of solidarity and enhance the South-South
cooperation at a time when we are confronted with common challenge,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
"To get united is the only way for developing countries to
enhance their status in the North-South dialogue, effectively
participate in making decisions related to world economy and
safeguard their own interests to the maximum in the course of the
globalization," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Though the economic globalization has presented us severe
challenges, it has also afforded us a big room for cooperation,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must seize the opportunity to continuously strengthen
coordination and cooperation in the financial, trade, debt and
other important economic areas, give play to our respective
strength to make up for our deficiencies, and broaden the sphere
of cooperation so as to tap the potential of the South-South
cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It has been proved that while continuing to deepen our
cooperation in traditional fields, we can very well expand it into
science and technology, education, investment and hi-tech
industries so as to inject new vigor and vitality into the South-
South cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The new situation requires new thinking and new approaches to
the South-South cooperation," he said. "To expand such cooperation
calls for vigorous support and big input from the governments of
all countries as well as the participation of the business
community and other quarters of society."
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary for all governments to formulate more pro-
active policies in the light of their specific national
conditional conditions, and support enterprises engaged in the
South-South cooperation with incentives," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The South-South cooperation should be open, allowing the
participation of international organizations and developed
countries," he said. "In the meantime, we should actively engage
ourselves in regional and sub-regional cooperation, which will in
turn help deepen and expand the South-South cooperation."
</P>
<P>
The South-South cooperation is among the four theme under
discussion at the South Summit, which opened here Wednesday to map
out a strategy for common development in the South in the new
century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000413.0372 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Development Calls for Fair, Rational New World Order, Li Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China said here Thursday that the
sound global development demands the establishment of a fair,
rational new international political and economic order as
developed countries are dominant in setting "rules of the games"
for world economy and most developing countries gained little from
the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing, head of the Chinese Government
delegation, made the statement in his speech at the first South
Summit, the largest gathering of heads of state and government of
the Group of 77 (G-77).
</P>
<P>
"The current world is undergoing major changes," Li said. "It
is moving towards multipolarity and generally towards relaxation."
</P>
<P>
"But it is by no means a world of peace and prosperity," he
said."The cold war mentality is still lingering on and hegemonism
and power politics are exerting themselves in new manifestations."
</P>
<P>
"The world has not acquired universal peace and economic
globalization now places development in a complex situation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the 1990s, economic globalization has
been developed rapidly, with a high growth of international trade,
increasingly bustling worldwide investment activities, accelerated
development of financial globalization and expeditious progress in
high-technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, "due to disparities in economic, scientific and
technological strength and development level, especially the
irrationality of the current international economic and political
order, the 'dividends' of the globalization have not been fairly
shared between the developed countries and developing countries,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Developed countries have benefited most from the globalization,
for they are in a dominant position in setting the "rules of the
games" for world economy, while most developing countries have
gained little from it and some are even being marginalized," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the gap between the North and the South is being
widened further, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"A shortage of development funds, heavy debt burden, worsening
trade terms and other such long-standing problems are still
plaguing the developing countries," he said. "Increasingly risks
of financial crises and the inadequacies in the international
financial system make things even worse for developing countries."
</P>
<P>
"They are faced with tremendous pressure and grave challenges
in terms of both economic security and economic sovereignty," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Economic globalization should benefit all countries and
peoples and should facilitate the common development of the whole
world," he said. "Its sound development calls for, more than ever,
the establishment of a fair and rational new international
political and economic order."
</P>
<P>
In such a new order, all countries should foster their mutual
relations in accordance with the purposes and principles of the U.
N. Charter and other universally recognized norms governing
international relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
In such a new order, all countries should have the right to
choose their social systems and development models in the light of
their respective national conditions and to fully participate in
making policies and regulations for world economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
In such a new order, all members of the international community
should, in a responsible manner and in a risk-sharing spirit, work
together closely to build a sounder and more effective
international
financial system and a more rational and balanced international
trade system, he said.
</P>
<P>
And in such a new order, the role of the United Nations should
be strengthened in the world economic policy-making process, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Economic globalization has made all countries in the world
more interdependent," he said. "To minimize the negative impact of
economic globalization, eliminate poverty and narrow the gap
between the North and the South are what developing countries are
striving to do and are also what developed countries must face
squarely."
</P>
<P>
"The wealth of the North should not and cannot be built on the
poverty of the South in a long run," he said. "Developed countries
must demonstrate their political will and adopt effective measures
to help developing countries out of difficulties."
</P>
<P>
"They should honor their commitments to reverse the declining
trend in providing official development assistance and provide
financial and technical support to developing countries without
attaching any political strings so as to help the latter increase
their capabilities for development," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They should fully implement the Uruguay Round agreements and
carry out to the letter provisions concerning special and
differential treatment to developing countries and give full
consideration to their concerns and interests in a new round of
multilateral trade negotiations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They should also reform the international financial system,
effectively monitor the hot money and help developing countries
enhance their ability to forecast and guard against financial
crises," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the South Summit, Li said that this is a "pioneering meeting.
"
</P>
<P>
"In the interest of safeguarding world peace and promoting
development, let us look back over the past and forward into the
future and work together in a cooperative spirit to map out a
strategy for common development in the new century," he said.
</P>
<P>
The South Summit, which opened here Wednesday, is believed to
be conducive to the stronger South-South cooperation to
collectively face the challenge of globalization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
