<HEADLINE> U.S. Refrains From Base Establishment in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
American authorities decided to operate from a Salvadorian
airport, before Costa Rica's resistance to allow military
operations within its territory.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Legislative Assembly, approved last year a Join
Patrol Law, which allows U.S. ships and military airplanes to
operate in national sea and air territory, in persecution of
aircraft suspected of carrying drugs.
</P>
<P>
The United States pretended to count as well with a land base
to supply its aircraft, and for that matter was considering Daniel
Oduber's airport at the city of Liberia, some 200 kilometers north
of San Jose as a possibility.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the U.S. embassy here did not want to make any
comments to this issue. Yet, Costa Rica's Public Security Minister
Rogelio Ramos told press that he received a call from the U.S.
Defense Department, confirming its decision.
</P>
<P>
It was preferred by the U.S. to make use of El Salvador's
Comalapa airport, where it reached an agreement for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that his country's decision does not affect
whatsoever join anti-drugs work carried out by both countries
since the beginning of last year within the frame of the Join
Patrol Law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
