<HEADLINE> Governor Bush Meets Republican Gays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican presumptive
presidential nominee George W. Bush met gay Republicans in Texas
Thursday in a bid to attract moderate voters.
</P>
<P>
The Texas governor declared that he was "a better person" for
hearing their stories although he said they still disagree on such
subjects as gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome gay Americans into my campaign," Bush said at a
press conference after the meeting. "It's important for the next
president to listen to people's real-life stories."
</P>
<P>
The Texas governor has been trying to moderate political image
after his appeals to religious conservatives helped him win South
Carolina's primary in February.
</P>
<P>
The 12-member invited gay group includes former Representative
Steve Gunderson of Wisconsin, and David Catania, District of
Columbia City Councilman.
</P>
<P>
"We went in with the hope and expectation that we would raise
his consciousness on certain issues," Catania said, "We think we'
ve done that."
</P>
<P>
Bush "was very interested in the idea" of having a gay speaker
at the Republican National Convention, Catania said.
</P>
<P>
At his press conference, Bush also confirmed reports that he
planned to meet with his former chief rival, Arizona Senator John
McCain, on May 9 in Pittsburgh.  
</P>
</TEXT>
