<HEADLINE> U.N. Office to Stay in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The resolution reaffirmed that a continued presence of the UNOA
"can contribute greatly to the promotion of peace, national
reconciliation, human rights and regional security".
</P>
<P>
The UNOA was established on October 15 1999 after a two year U.
N. Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA) ended in February last year.
UNOA is mandated to restore peace and assist the Angolan people in
the area of capacity-building and humanitarian relief.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Angola continued to deteriorate with refugee
influx along border areas with Namibia and Zambia, according to a
recent report by Annan.
</P>
<P>
The war-affected population because of a prolonged conflict
between the Government and the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) has now grown to 3.7 million out of
a total of 12.6 million in the African country. 
</P>
