<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Offers $10 Million To Caribbean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This was stated Thursday by Mark Malloch Brown, UNDP General
Administrator, during a working breakfast with the press in the
Southern Summit, that brought together 122 delegations of the
Group of 77.
</P>
<P>
Brown said that this project is supported by the Italian
government, adding that the donation is announced in a special
opportunity, in a summit that has the potentiality to have the
world commit itself in full with the desires of the poor countries.
</P>
<P>
"The debate can be moulded on the development for the new
millennium and obtain results in terms of a sustained human
development," he said.
</P>
<P>
UNDP reaffirmed Thursday its commitment to halve the figure of
the world population in poverty by the year 2015.
</P>
<P>
This occurs at a time in which the industrialized world
financial assistance to the poorest part of the planet has dropped
to less than 0.24 percent of the rich countries' gross domestic
product (GDP), compared to 0.33 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the UNDP had at that time 1.2 billion dollars,
dropping to only 700 million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Brown described six fields in which the UNDP expects to offer
advice on policies, and at the same time strengthen the national
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the first place the legislative institutions,
judicial systems, and municipal governments must be strengthened,
followed by the securing of a better performance of the government
directed to guarantee a bigger economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He said that to reduce poverty by 50 percent the developed
world as a whole needs to reach a per capital annual growth of at
least four percent, which would demand a global growth of some
seven percent.
</P>
<P>
In the third place, the widening of the gap between the rich
and the poor must be avoided, by means of the coordinated work of
the latter with UNDP and other world agencies, and expand the
public and private associations that will encompass the North and
the South, in the fourth place.
</P>
<P>
In the fifth and sixth places are the need not only of
increasing the national income, but also of eliminating illiteracy,
giving better opportunities to women and assuring human rights,
and in last place, to advance in the field of South-South
cooperation.  
</P>
