<HEADLINE> 118 South-South Cooperation Projects Presented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This was announced by Raul Taladrid, Cuban coordinator of the
South-South Cooperation Commission, giving the results of the
sessions in which the delegations of the 122 countries of the
Group of 77 (G-77) committed themselves to helping each other.
</P>
<P>
China ranked second after Cuba, which proposed 71 initiatives,
and joins Colombia, with three, Pakistan with seven, Bangladesh
with four, and Sri Lanka and Mauritania with one each.
</P>
<P>
The sessions of the panel occurred simultaneously with the
Southern Summit, which continued Thursday with the intervention of
the 42 heads of state and of government who took part in the first
summit meeting since the foundation of the G-77 in 1964.
</P>
<P>
Themes such as cooperation between municipalities of the North
and the South were discussed in that meeting, as a way to achieve
more fluid ways of exchange, without having to recur to the
central government.
</P>
<P>
Also discussed were the relation between the local dimension of
the development processes, the national programs and policies, and
the international projection, besides the support to the
communication strategies that will link the social and economic
advance with the targets of equity. 
</P>
