<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stock Markets Edge Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Europe's major stock markets
closed marginally higher Thursday after gains in leading telecom
companies across the region pared big losses on key indexes
earlier in the session.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index in London, the benchmark for Europe's
biggest stock market, gained 6.2 points, or 0.1 percent, to 6375.0,
recovering from an earlier drop of 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
British Telecommunications (BT) jumped 4.2 percent as investors
applauded news that it would demerge a new Yellow Pages and e-
commerce division this year as part of a broad restructuring aimed
at facilitating spin-offs.
</P>
<P>
BT said it is splitting its UK fixed-line business into
wholesale and retail divisions and reorganizing its other assets.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Vodafone AirTouch rose more than 2.7 percent,
extending Wednesday's gain, after the European Commission,the
executive arm of the European Union, cleared its 178 billion US
dollars takeover of Germany's Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft's woes kept several FTSE members in the red.Software
maker Sema Group dropped 4.6 percent and accounting software
company Sage Group shed 6.4 percent,while palm computer maker
Psion led the decliners on the FTSE 100, dropping 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The German Xetra Dax index ended flat on the back of a mixed
technology sector. The index ended at 7449.06 points, up 5.99 or 0.
08 percent.
</P>
<P>
The media-and technology-heavy CAC 40 in Paris rose 12.0 points,
or 0.2 percent, to 6250.70, after falling more than 2.7 percent in
morning trading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
