<HEADLINE> Tech Stocks Continue Falling In Fourth Consecutive Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A fear of inflation shattered
the technology stocks' advance Thursday, dragging the Nasdaq
composite lower in the fourth consecutive session.
</P>
<P>
At the close of session, the technology heavy Nasdaq composite
index fell 92.85 at 3,676.78. The composite rose as much as 145
points earlier in the trading.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 201.58 at 10,923.55 and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 26.66 at 1,440.51.
</P>
<P>
The stocks fell after a government report on rising wholesale
prices sparked fears of inflation. A big selloff started in the
blue chip sector and spread technology stocks later.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported that U.S. wholesale prices shot
up 1 percent in March, a worse showing on inflation than the 0.5
percent rise analysts have expected earlier.
</P>
<P>
Investors have jettisoned technology stocks in recent weeks,
driving the Nasdaq index down 27 percent as of Thursday from its
peak on March 10. This means the index has entered bear-market
territory, generally defined as a drop of 20% or more.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq's failure to sustain its early advance indicates
that investors were still nervous about prospects for technology
stocks which skyrocketed in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The late-day selloff overshadowed some good news on corporate
earnings for tech firms. Advanced Micro Devices, a leading
computer chip maker, reported its earnings at 1.15 U.S. dollars a
share in the first quarter, nearly twice 59 cents in expectations.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 9.64 at 644.61 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 11.56 at 915.23. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 4.22 at 489.22.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 11-to-8 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,721 down, 1,251 up and 486
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 1.03 billion shares from 1.14 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
